<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 92 / International Company News: Swiss to grant banking licences
to Japanese
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Swiss government is prepared to grant banking licences to up to 10
Japanese financial institutions by the end of this year.
Mr Alexis Lautenberg, head of the financial and economic division in the
Swiss Foreign Ministry, said yesterday that the government was also ready to
grant a one-year extension to the 11 other Japanese-owned non-bank financial
institutions in Switzerland which want to become banks but cannot yet
qualify.
These decisions reflect the successful conclusion of a lengthy bilateral
negotiation on financial issues between Japan and Switzerland.
The talks took place against the background of a Swiss law that requires all
non-bank financial institutions to convert themselves into banks by the end
of this year. The Swiss threatened to hold back banking licences unless the
Japanese Ministry of Finance (MoF) eased restrictions on the operations of
Swiss banks in Japan.
In late June, the Japanese Diet (parliament) passed a law enabling foreign
banks in Japan to increase their ownership of securities subsidiaries from
50 per cent to 100 per cent.
No progress was made on two other issues, The ministry refused to lift its
severe limits on Japanese individuals putting their capital in foreign
banks. 'We understand and trust they will take steps in the future,' Mr
Lautenberg said.
For legal reasons, the ministry has also been unable to lift restrictions on
securities companies' participation in the Japanese foreign exchange market.
The ministry will now decide to which financial institutions the Swiss
banking licences should be allocated. There is speculation in Japanese
financial circles in Zurich that all but one of the nine subsidiaries of
Japanese banks without banking licences will be selected, but only two of
the subsidiaries of the 12 securities companies will convert themselves into
banks.
Mr Lautenberg said the offer of an extension to the rest should only be
taken up by those who really intended to seek a banking licence. It should
not be used to delay making a decision.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 27
</PAGE>
