FT  08 JUL 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One day the journalists who currently make environmentalist programmes, all
of them belonging to the 'Have you stopped kicking kittens?' school of
manipulation, may be joined by somebody who approaches the subject in a
genuine spirit of inquiry.
Until then we will have to make do with programmes such as Costing The
Earth, which returns to Radio 4 today asking, among other things, whether
everyone is being brainwashed by green propaganda (7.20).
BBC2's six new documentaries States Of Mind are co-productions between the
BBC and American public service broadcasters, exploring American life via
different families.
Today's programme observes events in middle class Milwaukee through the eyes
of Fred Lach at the time of the trial of a man convicted of serial killings
(8.10).
BBC2's 'Screenplay' Force Of Duty (9.00) is a thriller set in Northern
Ireland. An RUC detective becomes obsessed with finding the terrorists who
killed his friend and police partner. Director Pat O'Connor previously
directed 'The Ballroom Of Romance', a superb television drama.
