FT  08 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: Row over health care is settled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS have settled a row that was threatening to delay the switch to
local authorities of responsibility for the government's care in the
community policies for the elderly and mentally handicapped, Philip Stephens
writes.
In what is seen as a defeat for the Treasury, health secretary Mrs Virginia
Bottomley is also close to winning her battle to ensure that money
transferred to local authorities from the social security budget to fund the
new system will be 'ring-fenced'.
The plans - which will begin next April to transfer to councils
responsibility for those requiring care at home or in residential
accommodation - have been the subject of intense Whitehall infighting.
The aim is to 'cap' a surge in open-ended income support payments to pay for
residential accommodation but the size of the initial transfer from the
social security to local authority budgets has been the subject of dispute.
The Treasury and the Department of the Environment have also opposed Mrs
Bottomley's view that the transfer can only succeed if local authorities are
prevented by ring-fencing from switching resources for community care to
other budgets.
The health secretary is now said to be confident that she has secured enough
money - several hundred million pounds - to ensure that the phasing in of
the new system can begin next year.
The government appears set to reject the recommendations of an independent
review body that more than 2,000 top public servants should receive a large
one-off pay rise to bring their salaries level with those in the private
sector.
Senior ministers said that they expect tomorrow's meeting of the cabinet to
scale back significantly the increases for senior civil servants, armed
forces officers and judges suggested by the Top People's Pay Review Board.
Mr John Major is also likely to insist that those pay awards of over 10 per
cent which are accepted by the government should be phased in.
