<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is encouraging the AEEU engineering and electrical union to
provide know-how to the nascent free trade unions of Romania, Michael Smith
writes.
The Foreign Office's 'know-how fund' has paid the expenses of Mr Nigel
Harris, an AEEU executive councillor, for an exploratory visit to the former
communist country. It has also agreed in principle to a two-week visit by
eight of the unions' officials.
The Foreign Office's know-how fund was set up in 1989 to provide technical
assistance for east European countries to adapt to market economies.
Although the AEEU money will have only a limited impact on the fund's annual
budget of Pounds 46m, its use may raise the eyebrows of some Tory MPs. The
AEEU is a moderate union but led the successful campaign for a 37-hour week
for engineering workers.
Mr Harris said that in Romania he and his colleagues would aim to show how
unions could operate in a market economy with a multi-party political
system.
The union's engineering section last year incurred a deficit of Pounds
949,714, according to its accounts published yesterday.
It was the third deficit in three years but the union expects staff
reductions and property sales to result in surpluses by 1993.
