<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JUL 92 / Fears grow of sharp rise in refugee numbers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MRS SADAKO OGATA, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, is due
to meet warring national leaders in Sarajevo today as continuing clashes
heighten fears the Bosnian refugee crisis could escalate further.
Some 1m people have been uprooted from their homes in four months of
fighting between Serb and Bosnian forces.
Ms Judith Kumin, the Belgrade representative of the UNHCR, said: 'The number
of refugees from Bosnia is increasing dramatically every day. We are very
concerned that it will continue. People who are now trapped in siege towns
will leave the minute they have to chance to seek safety.
'If Moslems continue to be forced from Serb-controlled territories, and
Serbs from regions controlled by Moslems, then the number of refugees will
be practically without limit.'
Serbs forces, which control more than half of Bosnian territory, are driving
out Moslems from eastern Bosnia in a policy of 'ethnic cleansing'.
Fighting eased yesterday in Sarajevo, the Bosnian capital besieged by Serb
forces. UN officials said that by mid-afternoon 15 relief flights had
arrived in the capital. They hope to fly in some 200 tonnes per day to feed
some 380,000 people trapped with little food and medicines.
Serb militias opposed to Bosnian independence yesterday fought against
mainly Croat and Moslem Bosnian forces around Brcko and Derventa, northern
Bosnia, according to Croatian radio. Belgrade radio said Serb forces had
clashed with Croat forces in Kupres, Hercegovina, where the Croats have
launched an offensive.
More than 7,500 people have been killed in Bosnia since it was widely
recognised as independent from Yugoslavia in April.
Mr Fred Eckhard, the spokesman for UN peacekeepers, yesterday said 93
prisoners were exchanged between Serb and Bosnian forces in the first
UN-sponsored exchange.
</TEXT>
