<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (3): Advanced details on the
autumn issue
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
To be published on Sept 11, 1992
The Autumn issue of Software At Work will examine users' experiences of
human resource systems, plus marketing and market research databases.
The 'hot topic' section will look at Europeanisation: the development of
software to serve different countries.
Here are details of the synopsis:
Human resource systems: payroll systems have been grinding away since the
early days of business computing, doing a dull but vital job.
The arrival of the personal computer raised the possibility of personnel
managers getting little administration systems of their own. But more
recently, payroll and personnel package users and suppliers have been
looking at exploiting basic data about employees to greater effect to help
plan, manage and use an organisation's biggest and usually most expensive
resource to maximum advantage.
Marketing and market research databases: marketing and selling demand the
right information to ensure the best return on effort. Market research
information is now available in a variety of forms, ranging from computer
bureau services to CDs which can be used with personal computers. What are
the options and how can the information best be used?
Europeanisation: the advent of the single European market is likely to bring
an increasing number of international mergers and partnerships, plus
overseas expansion by companies which have traditionally concentrated on
their home markets. This will bring demand for software running on different
computers which can handle multiple currencies and languages and the
oddities of different countries' business methods.
Following the September review, future issues of Software At Work will look
at developments in computer-aided design and manufacturing; document image
processing; project management; contingency planning and disaster recovery;
and electronic funds transfer at the point of sale.
For details of how Software At Work operates and how to contribute to the
next issue, see details in the article at the top of this page: Users have
their say. Information from users and suppliers is needed by Mon, July 13.
For a printed synopsis of the September issue, plus advertising information,
contact Polly Attwood at the Financial Times in London on 071 873 4685, fax
071 873 3079, or write to her at the Financial Times, Number One, Southwark
Bridge, London, SE1 9HL.
</TEXT>
