<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (1): The users have their say
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
This issue of Software At Work - the fifth in the FT's series of quarterly
software reviews - looks at three main topics:
Bespoke systems: software developed precisely for your company's needs,
rather than cheaper, standard packages.
Computer-related training for specialist staff.
The 'hot-topic': groupware - an extra level of applications software which
aims to create genuine interaction between people through a computer
network.
A strong emphasis of Software At Work is always to let the users have their
say. Once again, we have selected site visits and case studies with the hope
that these various approaches will help other software- users formulate
their own strategies.
For the site visits, our approach includes an overall report on how software
is chosen and applied, together with a company snapshot, describing its main
area of business.
Then for each site report there is a technology or system profile, listing
the software and hardware at the site. And, finally, we include in most
cases a consultant's critique on just how effective - or otherwise - the
system appears to be.
We hope to return to selected sites in future issues, to track their
progress. Sometimes today's success story is tomorrow's problem.
We also try to avoid technical jargon: this review is intended for the
executive decision-maker who may not have a technological background,
therefore a list of buzzword definitions is included on this page.
</TEXT>
