<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (32): The walk through the
warehouse no longer needed - Case Study / Hayward Promotions / Michael
Powell describes how a small children's book distributor is now able to
forecast with much greater accuracy the stock levels it should keep.
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL POWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVEN A relatively small business can benefit from custom additions to
standard packages. Hayward Promotions of Park Royal stocks and distributes
children's books and story tapes to the toy trade and prominent chain
stores.
The company, which was set up 10 years ago, uses the Multisoft accounting
package on its Elonex machine, running Xenix, and has a turnover of Pounds
1.6m.
According to Colin MacMillan, managing director of Hayward, the company
recognised that it had a stockholding problem in 1990.
The company deals in thousands of titles, and its control and forecasting
mechanisms were manual.
'We would walk around the warehouse to see what we had in stock, and act on
that. This would cause overstocking of some lines, and stock outs of others.
It's very annoying to have an order and not be able to fulfil it.'
Publishers only print a certain number of copies of a title, which can sell
out very quickly. If the correct number is not ordered, sales can be
permanently lost.
The company's Multisoft accounting system had a stock ledger, but there were
not sufficient analytical capabilities in it to allow Hayward to build
accurate forecasts of stock requirements.
To solve this difficulty, Mr MacMillan called in an old acquaintance, David
Halstead, of software house The Transition.
He designed a forecasting system which would be able to use a profile of the
company's monthly turnover to show where extra stock would be needed, to
cater for cyclical trends and sales patterns.
The system would use current turnover for each item and project future
turnover based on that. This would enable Hayward to buy in the correct
quantities of stock, based on demand.
The initial stage of the project was implemented over a period of three
months, and showed immediate benefits. Order fulfilment increased to 90 per
cent.
'One of the great bonuses for us was the reduction in time that our
management had to spend sorting out our mix of stock,' Mr MacMillan says.
The program was developed using a C programming language code generator
called Fred, from a UK company, Forefront.
According to Transition's sales manager, John Burden, C is used for
multi-platform support - 'we try to provide standard packages as much as
possible, with some bespoke portions where necessary.'
The program uses Multisoft's file structures for its data.
The development was done on a time and materials basis, bills being
presented and paid as it progressed. The total cost was around Pounds 4,000.
Transition is now adding demographic analysis of the population of parents
throughout the country. This will enable Hayward Promotions' agents to
target areas on which to concentrate their sales efforts.
'We can push a button to get data on best sellers and so on, to send to our
agents all over the country.
'There are 30,000 children's titles available, and we keep 6,000, so we
could not do this by hand. The system tells us what we need,' says Colin
MacMillan.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-14477</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1AG5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (30): Flexibility in the
securities business - Case Study / London Global Securities / A
recently-formed securities firm has used a fourth-generation language to
develop a fast-moving system for its own needs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL POWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SOFTWARE development requires more than just a clever programmer: it must
also have a great deal of input from the user or from an expert in the
field.
Indeed, using a fourth-generation language can significantly diminish the
amount of computer expertise required.
Moreover, in fast-moving businesses, advantage can be gained by being able
to develop a product more quickly than a competitor.
London Global Securities (LGS) is a securities lending intermediary which
was formed 18 months ago by experts in the market. It teamed up with
international software house K-Tek to produce a system.
'Like many of the players, we have used the Reuters Blend system until now,'
says director of operations, Stephen Jennett, 'but it's a bureau system. We
have spent the last 12 to 15 months specifying and building our own system,
which is in parallel running now and should go live in the next few weeks.'
K-Tek specialises in financial software systems for multi-national companies
which borrow and lend on, internationally. It has already installed a
general ledger system at LGS running on an IBM RS/6000. This will be fed
directly by the new administration system, once it is live.
K-Tek recommended the use of System Builder's SB+, a tool which uses Pick,
for this development.
Pick is a relational database-cum-fourth-generation language which offers a
high degree of portability and flexibility.
On LGS' RS/6000, this runs with the Universe Pick system - 'it's easy to add
reports, the system is very powerful and it looks like a PC,' says Mr
Jennett.
'The problem with the bureau system is that if we want to make a change we
have to tell the bureau. If it is acceptable, every other user benefits, so
we do not gain competitive advantage. The bureau has to be convinced that it
is to its advantage to make changes.'
However, Reuters Blend has enjoyed a monopoly until recently. Several larger
companies and software houses are working on their own products, but these
are not yet written. LGS believes it will be the first, because it is using
a fourth-generation language.
'We've no historical foundation to build in, because we're a young company.
We started later than some, but we are using up-to-date technology and
architecture.'
The product will be fully supported by K-Tek, which will also market it
under licence to other companies, with modifications or tailoring as
required.
Its name will be Global One, and there is already interest from US agents.
Using fourth-generation language techniques, the developers have brought
together software expertise, and the user experience of LGS, without
becoming bogged down in technicalities. The result is expected to be a
flexible product which should find a niche, and be ahead of its opponents.
Michael Powell
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-14478</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1AG4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (31): Sales staff are alerted to
future problems - Case Study / Wiggins Teape / Combining a relational
database with a fourth generation language has created a sophisticated new
order processing system
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
CUSTOMER service is often the key to success for commercial companies.
Achieving high levels of customer satisfaction often means that detailed
changes must be made to systems during their development. The choice of
development tools is crucial to this, writes Michael Powell.
Wiggins Teape is the largest paper merchant in the UK, part of the Arjo
Wiggins group. It developed a new order processing system which it calls
GENISYS (which stands for new GENeration of Information SYStems) to replace
a 14-year-old Assembler-based system, using Software AG's Natural
fourth-generation language (4GL), and IBM's relational database, DB2.
'DB2 is a strategic DBMS within this company, and Natural is a standard,'
says information systems director Russell Storey. 'It also gave Software AG
the opportunity to establish Natural/DB2.'
The development, started in 1990, is being performed by Software AG, at a
project cost of Pounds 1.5m. The initial feasibility study was performed by
consultants from Nolan Norton, which led to the decision to go for a bespoke
system.
Hoskyns was selected to do the systems design on a fixed price contract.
Wiggins Teape then went to the market again to tender for a developer.
Software AG offered the best deal and was selected.
Around 80 per cent of Wiggins Teape's sales orders come in through telephone
calls. The system provides all information needed to support the sale. For
instance, it displays action messages to alert sales people to potential
problems with orders. This enables them to provide a more focused service
using information based on exceptions.
A system on this scale cannot be introduced in one move - 'we don't believe
in big bangs,' says Mr Storey. The first phase, sales from stock, is
implemented.
The second phase, covering direct and indirect sales from third parties, is
being implemented, and the detailed work on the next phase, covering
accounts consolidation and stocking - back-office functions - is in
progress.
The entire project should be completed in September and will then have taken
some 25 man-years to develop.
The system handles around 2,500 transactions a day, and must provide good
information to the sales person, with reasonable response time - 'our
previous system was low on functionality, high on response time,' says Mr
Storey. 'The new system responds in around two seconds.'
He adds: 'We tend to be fairly cautious - state-of-the-shelf rather than
state-of-the-art. We do a lot of transactions and need to retain competitive
advantage, which means flexibility and the ability to make small changes to
the system to improve services to the customer. We've been able to modify
the system as we develop.
'Flexibility is the key word as far as we are concerned. That's why we went
for Natural, and a relational database - which lets us make changes without
massive re-structuring.'
Wiggins Teape is developing a complex, carefully designed system, using
high-level tools, which has enabled it significantly to improve the levels
of service to its customers.
The previous system did sterling service for many years but sacrificed
flexibility to fast response. The choice of 4GL and relational database has
enabled the company to retain flexibility during this development, without
compromising the overall design.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
