<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow reflects worries about US
economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
SHARE prices traded in a narrow range on either side of opening values
yesterday, as the markets digested the implications of last week's bad
economic news and the interest rate cut by the Federal Reserve, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 8.92 at 3,339.21. The
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was also little changed at the
finish, up just 2.07 at 413.84, as were the Amex composite, up 0.03 at
382.58 and the Nasdaq composite, 0.19 lower at 563.16. Turnover on the NYSE
was 187m shares.
Last week shares fell despite a big cut in interest rates by the Fed because
investors were more concerned with what the bad June employment figures said
about the state of the economic recovery. That concern continued to hamper
the market yesterday, and with the first batch of second quarter corporate
earnings due out soon, investors are likely to tread warily until they see a
clear sign of improvement in company profits and in economic activity.
Among individual stocks, consumer-related issues fared well in active
trading on hopes that they could be a good defensive play during tough
economic times. Philip Morris firmed Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 78 1/4 ,
Procter &amp; Gamble climbed Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 49 1/4 , Johnson &amp; Johnson
firmed Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 46 3/4 , Coca-Cola rose Dollars  5/8 to
Dollars 42 1/2 in turnover of almost 1.5m shares, and RJR Nabisco put on
Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 9 3/8 .
Banks were mostly weaker as analysts warned that competition for customer
accounts might prevent them from reducing their already low deposit rates in
the wake of the Fed's discount rate cut. Chemical fell Dollars 1 to Dollars
37 7/8 , Citibank by Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 20 3/4 , Chase Manhattan by
Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 27 3/4 and BankAmerica by Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars
44 5/8 .
Some of the broking stocks that rose after Thursday's rate cut also gave
back some of their gains, with PaineWebber easing Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 21
1/2 and Salomon falling Dollars 2 to Dollars 35 5/8 , although Merrill Lynch
recovered from early losses to end up Dollars 1/4 at Dollars 52 1/8 .
Airline stocks took off in expectation that approaching increases in fares
will boost flagging margins without damaging demand too much. Delta was
Dollars  3/4 higher at Dollars 55 1/4 , AMR, parent of American Airlines,
put on Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 66 1/4 , UAL was up Dollars  3/8 at Dollars
117 3/8 , USAir gained Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 13 1/8 and Southwest Airlines
rose Dollars 1 1/2 to Dollars 43.
On the Nasdaq market, FedFirst Bancshares jumped Dollars 4 1/2 to Dollars 33
1/2 after Southern National agreed to acquire the company in a stock-swap
deal worth Dollars 88.8m. Southern National fell Dollars 5/8 to Dollars 15
1/2 .
Canada
SHARE prices in Toronto closed slightly higher in relatively light trading.
Based on preliminary data, the composite index gained 6.77 points, or 0.20
per cent, to close at 3,426.91. Declines edged advances 274 to 243, trading
volume of 20.643m shares was above Friday's 15.021m shares, and trading
value was CDollars 242.6m against CDollars 166.9m.
The financial services group posted the day's biggest gain. Royal Bank was
up  1/4 to 24 3/4 , Bank of Montreal was up  1/2 to 47, Scotiabank gained
5/8 to 22 5/8 and Canadian Imperial Bank gained  5/8 to 28 3/4 .
</TEXT>
