FT  07 JUL 92 / Parliament and Politics: Advisers' fees in Maxwell probe may
be curtailed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SCALE of fees paid by Maxwell pension funds to professional advisers has
persuaded ministers that the unit led by Sir John Cuckney should be given a
role in co-ordinating the efforts of the various Maxwell pension funds in
recovering assets, in order to curtail their expenditure on fees to
professional advisers.
The unit's remit of helping to identify and remove areas of potential
overlap was spelt out by Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, in
a meeting yesterday with Mr Frank Field and Mr Richard Page, co-chairmen of
the all-party group of MPs campaigning on behalf of the Maxwell pensioners.
Mr Michael Meacher, the shadow social security secretary, has highlighted
the fact that the Maxwell pensioners have paid Pounds 5m in fees - twice the
amount set aside in the government's emergency arrangements to ensure that
no fund has to stop making payments. He has called for the government to pay
the fees itself.
The MPs came away from the meeting reassured that the government would not
cease the 'drip-feed' once the Pounds 2.5m runs out. Miss Ann Widdecombe,
the junior social security minister, told MPs in a written answer that so
far just under Pounds 300,000 had been paid to trustees of the Maxwell
Communication Works Pension Scheme and of the Headington Pension Plan.
Ms Majorie Mowlam, Labour's voice on the City, expressed anger that the
trust fund for Maxwell pensioners has still not been set up four weeks after
it was announced.
In a separate written answer, Miss Widdecombe said the trust deed would be
prepared once the terms of the trust had been agreed. There was pressure
yesterday for ministers to consult the director of public prosecutions and
the Serious Fraud Office on guidelines to avoid 'unnecessary humiliation' of
potential defendants in high-profile cases. Concern follows last month's
arrests of Mr Kevin Maxwell and Mr Ian Maxwell.
