<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Canals may help combat droughts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SHORTAGE of water in eastern and south-east England, made acute by low
rainfall in the past three years, could be alleviated by transferring
supplies by canal from areas with ample resources.
British Waterways, responsible for the canal system in England and Wales,
said yesterday it was commissioning a feasibility study into whether
millions of gallons of water could be diverted into canals and transferred
south without damaging animal and plant life or affecting recreational use.
Consultants are expected to be chosen within two months and their study
should be completed in about nine months. Until then, British Waterways
intends to continue talks with water companies and the National Rivers
Authority (NRA), the rivers watchdog, to assess who needs more water and who
would pay for its transfer by canal.
Mr David Ingman, British Waterways chairman, said initial studies showed it
would be several times cheaper to improve the channels of its canals than to
build long-distance pipelines to form a national water grid.
He said: 'We approached the NRA more than a year ago with our ideas and we
could be up and running within five years. The next step is a full
engineering and environmental feasibility study which is essential before
volumes of water could flow, and we are now in the process of seeking
tenders from major consultancies.'
One preferred option is for water from the north-west to be diverted south
via the Shropshire Union, Trent &amp; Mersey, Coventry, Oxford and Grand Union
canals to the rivers Nene and Great Ouse serving East Anglia, and down to
the Thames. Other possible sources are the Cambrian Mountains in Wales and
Kielder reservoir in Northumberland.
The feasibility study will consider the effect of extra water on locks,
bridges and aqueducts; the number, location and cost of pumping stations;
the protection of wildlife, fisheries, heritage and architecture, and the
maintenance of water quality and the character of affected canals.
Mr John Taylor, British Waterways water development manager, said supplies
destined for public use had been flowing along canals for many years. At
present, 148m gallons a day were carried, including 45m gallons which met
half Bristol's daily requirement. The initial plan would add about 60m
gallons, but other schemes could be added.
The rivers authority welcomed the feasibility study and said it would
consider any proposals to alleviate water shortages. Mr Jerry Sherriff, head
of water resources at the authority, said the proposal did not offer a
'quick-fix' solution, but it could be implemented more quickly than some
other options such as regional grids and desalination plants.
Curbs on water use because of the drought affect 6.75m people. The drought
is considered to be the worst in parts of the south and east since records
began in the mid 1700s.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-14538</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1AFGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Polls on water metering 'mislead'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
WATER METERING would be less popular if consumers knew the full cost and how
much water was lost through leakage, the National Consumer Council warned
yesterday.
Surveys carried out for Ofwat, the water industry regulator, suggest
widespread public support for metering.
However, Mr Robin Simpson, deputy chairman of the council, says in Consumer
Voice magazine that the surveys were misleading. 'In none of the surveys
were the respondents told that the average leakage is about 25 per cent of
the water supplied by the water companies.'
About 64 per cent of 290,000 respondents to a questionnaire sent to 18m
homes said they would prefer metering. But Mr Simpson said: 'The
questionnaire gave a range of increases in water charges due to metering,
with an increase of Pounds 29 a year at the top end. Yet there are
well-documented cases where water charges have increased by more than that.'
Water companies have three options after the present system is phased out:
metering; a flat licence fee; and a bill based on the type of property.
Ofwat said that with metering - the fairest option - customers would pay for
leakages only if they were in their own supply pipes - not any in the mains.
The director-general of Ofwat should have powers to compel companies to
compensate customers for poor service, the chairmen of Ofwat's regional
customer service committees said yesterday.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
