<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-14539</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1AFFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Safeway will drop secrecy about product sales data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SAFEWAY, the UK's third biggest grocery chain, is to sell sales data on
every product category in its 322 stores as part of an initiative to develop
closer relationships with suppliers.
The company has formed a joint venture with Nielsen, the market-research
group, to collate sales information from the electronic point-of-sale (Epos)
equipment in its stores.
Safeway claims to be the first of the big grocery chains to scan every sale
made in its stores.
The information is likely to be eagerly sought by manufacturers of consumer
products, because they can use the information to adjust production levels
and assess promotions.
Until now, most of the big grocery chains have closely guarded their sales
data, believing that it could be of value to competitors and that it is,
therefore, of considerable commercial sensitivity.
Mr David Coles, Safeway's marketing director, said it was an appropriate
time to start sharing sales information with suppliers as closer links
developed between retailers and manufacturers. The data would provide a
'common language' which could benefit both parties. 'We are looking for ways
to develop more of a partnership relationship with our suppliers so that
they can manage alongside us, rather than being kept at a distance,' he
said.
Safeway sells between 15,000 to 20,000 different lines in its stores and has
about 6m customers a week.
The Safeway/Nielsen service will start reporting sales data by the end of
the year.
The cost of access to the service has not been finalised, but Mr Coles said
the rate would be 'flexible'.
Asda results, Page 21
