<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Recession blamed for policy cash-ins
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INSURANCE companies, stung by criticism from the regulators, yesterday said
that the recession had been the biggest single factor in early surrender of
long-term life policies.
But Mr Keith Bedell-Pearce, director of Prudential and chairman of the group
of nine companies which commissioned research, admitted that the life
insurance industry 'must do better'.
The companies outlined measures to ensure that fewer policies are sold to
those for whom they are inappropriate and to ensure that consumers
understand the risks of long-term policies. Figures published by the
companies found that more than a third of customers said they were not told
about the financial implications of allowing a policy to lapse. In the first
five years of a 25-year policy, often used to back a mortgage, the surrender
value will usually be significantly less than the total premiums.
A survey by the Securities and Investments Board at the end of last year
found that during 1990, 37.1 per cent of unit-linked life policies and 23
per cent of with-profits policies were terminated within two years of being
started.
Mr Bedell-Pearce said: 'There was a very clear message that the rate of
persistency had deteriorated, and that they were unacceptable. It was also
clear that no hard reasons yet existed.' The companies intended to change
the selling techniques in order to ensure that customers understood that
they could lose money by surrendering their policies.
They would also follow their report's recommendation that product design
should be altered to allow policyholders more flexibility when affected by
events such as redundancy or divorce.
The survey found that 68 per cent of customers gave up their policies
because of a 'change in personal circumstances'. The main reasons within
these were inability to continue paying premiums (15 per cent), redundancy
(10 per cent) and a need for extra cash (7 per cent).
However, 14 per cent of surrenders came as a direct result of problems with
advisers or with service direct from the life office, while 17 per cent were
caused by complaints about value for money.
The insurance companies whose customers were interviewed were: Commercial
Union, Eagle Star, General Accident Life, Guardian Royal Exchange, Legal &amp;
General, Norwich Union, Prudential, Royal Life, and Sun Alliance.
The research was carried out by Survey Research Associates, and 7,569 people
were interviewed.
</TEXT>
