FT  07 JUL 92 / National Savings launches new bond
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL Savings yesterday fulfilled Mr Norman Lamont's Budget promise of a
new product by launching a one-year fixed-rate bond.
However, Mr Tim Melville-Ross, chief executive of Nationwide Building
Society, said the rate was 'a bit strong' and was not helpful in enabling
building societies to cut mortgage rates.
FIRST (Fixed Interest Rate Savings Tax-Paid) Option Bond goes on sale today
with a guaranteed interest rate of 7.75 per cent net (equivalent to 10.34
per cent gross) on a minimum of Pounds 1,000. Tax is deducted at source and
the bond is aimed at the country's 25.1m basic-rate taxpayers. A higher rate
of 8.05 per cent is payable on Pounds 20,000 and above.
Mr Anthony Nelson, economic secretary to the Treasury, said it was aimed at
funding the government's public sector borrowing requirement this year of
Pounds 28bn. He said that in setting the rate, the government had been
mindful of protests from banks and building societies that National Savings
rates were too high.
National Savings has outperformed building societies for several months of
this year. In May, National Savings recorded net receipts of Pounds 333m
against net receipts of Pounds 179m by building societies. The Building
Societies' Association said yesterday that the new bond 'will provide more
competition for savings.'
National Savings contributed a net Pounds 3.1bn to government funding last
year and it has already raised Pounds 1.5bn in the first quarter of the
year.
Halifax, the UK's largest building society, which launched a similar product
in May, the Guaranteed Reserve, said yesterday that it had anticipated
public demand for the bond and believed its own product offered 'attractive
and realistic rates of interest'.
