<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Doctors open the debate on care rationing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S doctors yesterday opened the way to involving the government and
the public in discussions on one of the most sensitive of medical issues,
the rationing of health care.
The British Medical Association plans a national conference early next year
and intends to invite senior ministers.
Dr Jeremy Lee-Potter, chairman of the association's council, said the
conference would also draw speakers from a wide range of backgrounds
including doctors, philosophers, economists and patients.
'Rationing health care is not a party political issue,' he told the
association's annual conference in Nottingham. 'It is an unavoidable fact of
life and there is no doubt in my mind that it must be done openly.'
There is growing recognition by governments that not all medical demands can
be met with equal speed and that some form of priority setting is required.
This has been done most controversially in the state of Oregon in the US
where the authorities have developed a league table of medical and surgical
priorities related to available funds.
In the UK, the separation of healthcare purchasing from its provision under
last year's health reforms is making health authorities more critical about
allocation of resources, bringing the issue higher up the National Health
Service agenda.
Delegates at the association's conference supported a motion declaring that
the rationing of health services was 'an unfortunate fact of life' and that
it should be done openly by agreement between the Department of Health and
the medical profession.
Dr Lee-Potter said that the issue of rationing had to be faced as a matter
of urgency, with clear guidelines agreed to bring consistent decisions on
medical and surgical priorities throughout the NHS. Healthcare resources
would always be finite while demands for services were not.
A number of speakers in the debate supported this view but opponents, such
as Dr Tony Hicklin from Surrey, argued that if the association endorsed the
principle of rationing, ministers would regard it as the medical
profession's agreement to 'any cuts in funding they decide to make'.
Leaders of the association hope that opening up the debate on priorities may
draw renewed attention to the relatively low level of GDP devoted to health
care in the UK, which they regard as the NHS's worst structural problem. Dr
Lee-Potter said that rationing 'must never be allowed to become another word
for underfunding'.
</TEXT>
