<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / BT bars many redundancy applicants: Voluntary package
oversubscribed Unions say workforce is further demoralised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of British Telecom-munications employees who want to leave their
jobs as part of a voluntary redundancy programme are being told they will
have to stay. Unions say the move has provoked fury among BT's employees and
has further demoralised an already insecure workforce.
BT is spending more than Pounds 1bn on Release 92, its scheme to shed 24,000
employees this year from a workforce of 200,000. However, terms are so
attractive and, the unions claim, morale so low that the redundancy scheme
is heavily oversubscribed.
BT intended to cut 8,000 engineering jobs but 17,000 engineering staff want
to take voluntary redundancy. A total of 7,000 clerical workers want to
leave compared with a target figure of 2,000.
Half the total workforce initially expressed an interest in receiving more
information. The deadline for final acceptance under the scheme is the end
of next week.
The National Communications Union, the main BT union, says some members have
already bought small businesses, put their homes on the market or made plans
to emigrate on the strength of indications from management that attractive
redundancy terms would be available.
Under Release 92 payments could be as high as Pounds 100,000 plus pension
entitlement, although the average sum is likely to be about Pounds 30,000.
Training vouchers worth Pounds 1,000 and at least three months' guaranteed
work through an employment agency are also on offer.
Because of the demand BT is introducing criteria for redundancy selection.
Those who have gained high marks in performance appraisals will not normally
be eligible for the scheme, and those with long service will also go to the
bottom of the list because of the high costs of paying them off.
Mr Bill McClory, NCU assistant secretary, said it was clearly prejudicial to
his members' interests to be good at their jobs.
The Union of Communication Workers, whose members in the operator service at
telephone exchanges are threatened by future job cuts, added that there had
been a high level of interest from operators.
BT said yesterday it had made clear from the outset that management 'would
ultimately have to decide whether or not it could allow an applicant to go.
People should not have made any firm plans for their future until they had
received confirmation that they could go, been given a confirmation of their
entitlements and made a formal decision to accept the offer.' It added that
further job reductions were likely, although no specific posts had been
identified. The terms of Release 92 were unlikely to be repeated under any
future redundancy scheme, said BT.
</TEXT>
