<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / World Trade News: Financing fixed for third section of
Algeria-Italy pipeline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ALGIERS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FINANCING for the Dollars 260m (Pounds 136m) third section of a new
Algeria-to-Italy gas pipeline, to be built by Transmediterranean Pipeline
Co, has been completed after eight banks have agreed to underwrite the
venture.
Transmediterranean, a Jersey-based venture between Snam, the gas and
petroleum subsidiary of ENI, Italy's state-owned energy group, and
Sonatrach, Algeria's state-owned hydrocarbons company, is building the
pipeline beside an existing pipe from Algeria, through Tunisia and the
Sicily Channel, to Italy. Snam has been buying gas from Sonatrach since 1983
and is contracted to buy 530bn cu m by 2019, one of the world's biggest
energy supply pacts.
Morgan Grenfell has been working since October to bring eight banks together
to finance the third section of the pipe, through the Sicily Channel, where
work is due to begin soon.
The two facilities comprise a Dollars 200m Italian buyer credit guaranteed
by SACE, the Italian export credit agency, and a Dollars 60m commercial
loan. Financing was secured for the trans-Tunisian section last year, and
financing for the Dollars 400m Algerian section is expected to be in place
by the end of this year. The pipeline will contribute significantly to
Italy's energy needs.
Reuter reports from Algiers: Sonatrach has signed an agreement with BP
Exploration of the UK to study ways of co-operating in oil and gas
exploration and production.
Sonatrach, seeking foreign partners to increase oil and gas output, said the
two also agreed to look into co-operating in selling and transporting
natural gas in Europe.
BP's chief executive, Mr Richard Newton, signed the pact after talks with
Algeria's oil minister, Mr Nordine Ait-Laoussine and Sonatrach's
director-general, Mr Abdelhak Bouhafs.
Sonatrach said negotiations were also being held to finalise a contract for
exploring in Algeria's Atlas Tellien mountains. The range divides Algeria's
north coastal region from the Sahara desert.
</TEXT>
