<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / The Munich Summit: Leaders shrink from force in Yugoslavia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADERS of the Group of Seven industrialised countries are tomorrow due to
adopt a separate declaration on Yugoslavia, leaving open the use of military
force as a last resort to back up United Nations sanctions and relief
operations.
It will make clear that such a decision can be taken only by the UN Security
Council.
At a dinner meeting last night, President Francois Mitterrand of France
argued strongly in favour of installing non-UN troops on the road from
Sarajevo airport to the city. These troops would protect convoys carrying
humanitarian aid into the city and would be empowered to shoot if necessary.
But Mr John Major, UK prime minister, said that Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali,
the UN secretary-general, was worried that the plan could lead to confusion
between UN and non-UN troops, and so endanger the lives of UN troops. This
was one of the issues still unresolved last night.
Mr Enzo Scotti, the Italian foreign minister, said the G7 leaders also
discussed a possible naval blockade to enforce UN sanctions against Serbia.
Officials from the nine-nation Western European Union have already been
examining contingency naval plans. WEU foreign ministers may discuss the
idea further at a special meeting in the margins of the 52-nation summit of
the Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe (CSCE) in Helsinki
later this week.
British officials, however, stressed that the question of military action
did not arise at the moment. They said it would become an option only if
humanitarian aid to Bosnia was not getting through, which was not the case
at present.
The G7 leaders also discussed new French and Italian proposals for
transforming the European Community's peace conference on Yugoslavia,
chaired by Lord Carrington, into a wider international conference under the
umbrella of the UN.
But it was not clear whether this proposal would figure in the planned
declaration on Yugoslavia.
Meanwhile, officials in the besieged Bosnian capital of Sarajevo said
yesterday the international relief effort was not stopping fighting or
preventing Bosnia from being divided between Croatia and Serbia.
According to Croat television, Serb forces have captured the strategic town
of Derventa in central Bosnia, setting houses ablaze.
Relief agencies said Serbs had also seized control of a string of towns in
eastern Bosnia, on or near the Serbian border. Moslems in the region had
been killed, imprisoned or forcibly deported.
Refugees who escaped from Gorazde, eastern Bosnia, say there are hardly any
Moslems left in the town, though they used to make up 70 per cent of the
population.
The Serbian offensive coincided with the formation at the weekend of a new
Croatian state in western Hercegovina.
A British official said the new state, backed by the government in Zagreb
under President Franjo Tudjman, 'would not be recognised'. He said western
diplomats might now be pushed into considering sanctions against Croatia in
view of Zagreb's attempts to undermine UN peacekeeping operations in
Croatia, and its de facto annexation of western Hercegovina.
Mr Milan Panic, the California-based businessman who last week was appointed
prime minister of the new Yugoslavia, consisting only of Serbia and
Montenegro, appealed in Belgrade yesterday for a delay of 100 days to
determine the status of the country at the Conference on Security and
Co-operation in Europe.
In a letter to CSCE delegates, he said his goal was to stop the fighting.
The US and other countries want to exclude Yugoslavia from the CSCE which
starts a two-day summit in Helsinki on Thursday.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
