<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / The Munich Summit: IMF chiefbacks Moscow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMF managing director, Mr Michel Camdessus, yesterday strongly urged G7
finance ministers to back the phased reform plan he has agreed with the
Russian government.
He also insisted that the plan still complied with Russia's reform promises
last April.
He stopped short of urging them to agree a debt rescheduling for Russia,
still under negotiation in the Paris Club of official creditors, although he
said President Boris Yeltsin was entitled to ask for creditors'
understanding.
Mr Camdessus, who flew from Moscow to brief the ministers before Mr Yeltsin
arrives tonight, spelt out the broad conditions agreed by the Russian
government. It was up to Mr Yegor Gaidar, prime minister, to reveal details,
he said.
However, he said that on the controversial question of energy price
liberalisation, both sides had agreed on a progressive approach of freeing
the prices gradually.
'Liberalisation, especially of energy prices, is one of the key elements
agreed by us with Russia in April,' he said. 'What the Russians do not want
to do (and we agree) is to liberalise energy prices all of a sudden. At the
moment the gap between the world energy price, and domestic prices, is too
huge.'
As for debt rescheduling, both Mr Camdessus and Mr Theo Waigel, German
finance minister, refused to prejudge the decisions of the Paris Club.
However, it is clear that the G7 wants to do a deal if details can be
agreed. 'Russia I believe will continue to enjoy the support of the Paris
Club, and explain what it is doing at the next meeting,' Mr Camdessus said.
</TEXT>
