<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Major moves to rescue Gatt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN and ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MUNICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday put forward proposals to break the logjam of the
stalled round of trade liberalisation talks in the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade.
During a day of intensive discussions on the future of the Uruguay Round at
the economic summit of the Group of Seven leading industrial nations, Mr
Major made what British officials described as a forceful intervention in
the opening session.
His officials refused to give further details but Mr Don Mazankowski, the
Canadian finance minister, later disclosed that the UK prime minister had
brought forward proposals which he expected to be discussed later in the
summit. The proposals are thought to include an extension of the period for
reduction of farm subsidies.
Mr Major's decision to bring the Uruguay Round to the heart of the summit
involves a high-risk strategy that reflects the British government's
determination to find a settlement, and to put Britain's stamp on the EC
presidency.
Even before Mr Helmut Kohl, the German chancellor, had completed the
ceremonial welcome of the leaders of the US, Japan, France, Britain, Italy,
Canada and the European Commission, the Gatt talks were a subject of intense
discussion.
The issue was raised amid concern about the lacklustre growth of the world
economy and rising unemployment. Mr Mazankowski noted that unemployment in
the Group of Seven countries had risen to 22.9m this year from 18m in 1990.
Finance ministers meeting separately agreed that the only way forward was to
curb excessive budget deficits and strive for stable non-inflationary
growth.
Mr Norman Lamont, the UK chancellor, confirmed that Britain would take an
especially tough line on government spending in the current expenditure
round.
He pledged again to take sterling into the narrow bands of the European
exchange rate mechanism at the current DM2.95 central rate as part of the
British government's continuing fight against inflation.
Mr Nicholas Brady, the US treasury secretary, conceded that US growth in the
second quarter of this year would not match expectations but that expansion
of between 2.5 per cent and 3 per cent over the full year was attainable.
He also predicted 'banner years' for the economy in 1993-94 if the
commitment to growth to be undertaken at this summit is fulfilled.
In a summit where all the nations are intent on maintaining their own
economic policies, the leaders and their finance ministers underlined that a
satisfactory solution to the trade talks could be an important spur to world
growth.
According to British officials, a success in the Gatt talks would add
between 1 per cent and 2 per cent to world gross national product.
Mr Major cited calculations that a Gatt success would add Dollars 200bn to
annual world income of which Dollars 90bn would accrue to developing
nations.
THE MUNICH SUMMIT
