<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Dentists vote to freeze NHS lists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 25m patients not already registered with a dentist will find it
harder to get NHS treatment and may have to pay for private treatment, after
dentists voted for partial withdrawal from the National Health Service.
The dentists are responding to government plans to cut their fees by 7 per
cent from tomorrow. Some are likely to withdraw from NHS work altogether.
Two-thirds of members voted in separate ballots of two dentists'
associations, the results of which were announced yesterday, and neither of
which is binding.
Mrs Virginia Bottomley, health secretary, yesterday urged dentists to think
'long and hard' before taking action which would jeopardise NHS dental
treatment. She pledged to take 'all necessary steps' to safeguard NHS dental
services.
Members of the 16,000-strong British Dental Association voted to stop taking
all new NHS patients - including children and people on low incomes who
would be eligible for free NHS treatment. A proposal to remove adult NHS
patients from members' lists was defeated, with 55 per cent voting against.
The 4,000 members of the General Dental Practitioners' Association voted to
withdraw all NHS services from patients not entitled to free treatment.
There is unlikely to be a rapid exodus from the NHS, with both associations
warning against hasty action. Scope to opt out of the NHS may also be
limited in some areas, where private practice may not be viable.
The BDA described the future of NHS dentistry as 'bleak', and both
associations appealed to the government to avert the crisis. Dentists'
leaders said the government was effectively privatising NHS dentistry by
forcing practitioners out of the health service through the cuts in fees.
Mrs Bottomley said she regretted the dentists' ballot decisions in reply to
an emergency question in the Commons from Mr Robin Cook, Labour's shadow
health secretary.
Detailed arrangements for a 'fundamental review' would be announced shortly,
she said. It would aim to 'find a system which is fair to dentists, fair to
patients and fair to the NHS'.
The government claims the fee cuts are needed because dentists are earning
more than the target income set by the doctors' and dentists' pay review
body. Dentists' negotiators say earnings have risen because they have
registered more patients and that cuts will lead to bankruptcies.
Dentists take preventive action, Page 7
</TEXT>
