<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (40): Training courses, time well
spent - Consultant's Viewpoint / For patient trainees, most computer
training courses offer big benefits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL POWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS a freelance consultant, I do not often have the opportunity to attend
training courses. Time is precious, and I find it more efficient to train
myself whenever possible.
Since I also, on occasions, present courses, I am more accustomed to giving
than to receiving - so it was a rare luxury to be invited to attend the
training course on Recital given by Richfords Computer Services. The company
provides 'hands-on' training on many different database products, and on
programming in 'C'.
They are located in the South Bank Technopark, at London's Elephant and
Castle area. At this course, each of the attendees was seated in front of a
terminal, which is connected to a Unix machine.
I had reviewed and used the product in an earlier version. It is one of the
'xBase' family of database management-cum-programming languages. I have some
recent experience of the excellent Foxpro product, so understand the
principles. Recital is unique in being available under many versions of Unix
and Dec's VMS.
It has some differences from the other xBase products - additions which make
it unique, such as its data dictionary.
We were led through a rather slow introduction - slow for me and two of the
other three, but the fourth had less experience, so the course was naturally
run at his pace. But this was no great disadvantage, because I was able to
play around with the machine, exploring both Recital and Unix, which I had
not used for about a year.
This led to an embarrassing moment, when I managed to freeze my terminal
whilst trying out one of the games I had found - and I couldn't remember how
to clear the problem. Unfortunately, neither could the instructor, and his
only recourse was to restart the whole system.
When I stupidly did the same the next day, I had remembered how to sort it
out, but I still had to ask for his help.
The course was accompanied by a very competent manual. This covered each
topic, both giving practical padding to the instructor, and amplifying what
was being said.
The instructor, Neil Blakemore, was suitably knowledgeable, and efficiently
led us through the examples. As a trainer you always have a dilemma. Do you
assume the attendees have read the page you have pointed them to, or do you
read it to them?
I usually try to paraphrase its content, so that it does not sound as if I
am teaching by rote. Neil Blakemore did this nearly every time, but very
occasionally inspiration would fail him and he would fall back on reading
the page back to us.
The advantage of having a terminal in front of you in such a course is that
you can explore subjects at your own pace, once you have finished the set
sections.
I was unable to attend the last day, but was anxious to try out some
programming, and was pleased to be able, during the lunch hours, to mess
around and do some of the examples from the last day's notes. I also have
the manual, and can lead myself through the rest of the course on my own
machine. Incidentally, Richfords provided a very adequate sandwich lunch.
I've been on courses where this is not provided: the attendees wander off to
the local hostelry, and then come back late and sleep the afternoon away.
But by providing food, you can control this tendency. You can also give
students the chance to explore the system, catch up with parts they may have
missed or misunderstood.
Some observers may arge that time spent on courses is not always well spent
 -particularly when you have a comprehensive set of notes, so that you can
often teach yourself perfectly adequately. However, for more patient
students, most courses have great value. You are led along at a sensible
pace, uninterrupted by telephone and colleagues. You have the attention of a
person with expertise in the subject who can answer your questions, without
you having to go to the manual. Moreover, his answers will be more focussed
and comprehensive.
My main reason for attending this course was to prepare myself for some work
in Recital. I believe that it achieved its aim. I now know my way round the
system, and have some notes to help me to explore it further.
THE NEXT ISSUE of Software at Work will appear on September 11, 1992.
For advance details of the topics to be covered, see page two of this issue.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
