<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (39): GUIs bring training
advantages - Impact of Graphical User Interfaces (GUIs) / Much of the pain
of learning basic computer skills is removed with graphical user interfaces.
They also reduce the learning curve on training staff for new applications
software
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GRAPH below shows the dramatic impact of graphical users interfaces
(GUIs) on the learning curve for new computer applications.
It was first published by Apple Computer a couple of years ago to highlight
one of the advantages of the Macintosh personal computer and its innovative
GUI software. But following the success of Microsoft Windows, the GUI for
IBM-compatible personal computers, the graph has a much wider relevance.
It shows that the learning curve for a user getting to know their first
application is steep - as one would expect. But when users move on to a new
application, the curve is shallower - because they are able to transfer
knowledge of one application to another.
The skills they have learned in a word processor - like saving a file or
re-formatting text - can be used in the same way in a spreadsheet or a
desktop publishing package. This is a direct result of the use of standard
GUIs and the influence they have brought to bear on applications software
developers. By their very nature GUIs are easier to use than previous
interfaces. And they force developers to use standard methods of doing
things, which works to the benefit of the user.
The basic controls for all software applications are the same in a GUI
environment - similar to the way that controls on a 35mm camera or a motor
vehicle are consistent across different manufacturer's products.
This has significant implications for training - particularly in the area of
basic IT skills training. In the future, GUIs will help to enforce standards
across applications and make both the users' and the trainers' job much
easier. Attention can be focussed on the application, rather than on the
demands of the technology.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXIV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-14593</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1ADXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (38): Sceptics persuaded by
careful training - Case Study / Northern Electric was faced with complex
training problems when it equipped its sales force with laptop computers.
But a carefully designed training programme brought success and helped it to
keep its experienced sales staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NORTHERN ELECTRIC, the northern UK power utility, decided to use IT to
support its sales and marketing operations following privatisation. It
wanted systems which could back up its sales force with up-to-date customer
information and capture data for market research purposes.
Training the sales force to use the technology effectively was crucial to
the project's success - especially given the nature of the established sales
force and the change in Northern Electric's business.
The hub of the sales and marketing system is a large ICL mainframe which
administers a database of Northern Electric's customers - covering domestic,
commercial and industrial. The mainframe uses an Ingres database management
package to handle the data and act as a 'server' to smaller computers at the
various regional offices.
'The system contains a complete model of the sales and mark eting
life-cycle,' explains Tim Crick, the project manager at Northern Electric.
'We can use it to find market opportunities - for things like direct mail
shots or for placing advertising.'
The front-end of the system relies on the sales force equipped with laptop
computers. Each night the laptops are connected to the electricity supply
and the telephone system and 're-charged.' The mains re-charges the
batteries and the telephone line transmits customer data for future sales
visits from the regional offices.
The laptops also contain software to work out sales quotations for central
heating systems and other products - as well as taking orders from
customers. The orders are transmitted back to the regional office during the
overnight 're-charge.'
Northern Electric was faced with a complex problem when it came to training
the sales force. The wide range of age and experience - from bright
20-year-old novices to 60-year-old veterans - and the different levels of
computer awareness, led Northern Electric to use a multi-level approach.
'Our industry is going through great change after a long period of
stability. Some of our sales staff have worked the same way for many years
and we knew we had to change this - and the culture around it,' says Mr
Crick.
'We asked Kernel Training to help us design a programme which was selective
and could help everyone - and bring them all up to the same level of
competence.'
Kernel Training (now FI Training) specialises in training programmes for
custom-built applications software and had been used to help with previous
training projects at Northern Electric.
Tim Crick says that it was important to get users involved early in the
project: 'We began with a public relations exercise when we were actually
developing the system with a review group and a clear role for people from
the sales force right from the beginning.'
The next stage was to instruct the sales force in how to use the laptop
computers: 'We ran computer familiarisation courses for those with no
previous experience - how to turn the machine on, how to re-charge it,
things like that. And we gave them a machine to take home with packages that
they could explore for themselves.'
Tim Crick adds that 'a couple of games' were included in the package to
break novice users in gently.
The basic familiarisation phase was followed by workshop sessions on the
applications software and a role-playing 'dress-rehearsal.'
'We took the sales people to a show-house and went through a role-playing
exercise to let them see how it worked in a real sales situation,' he says.
By this stage, some of the sales force were ready to 'fly solo' - while
others needed more instruction and confidence building, says Mr Crick.
'It was more often a lack of confidence and seeing the laptop as an aid
which some staff found hard.'
The important lesson learned by Northern Electric is that the multi-level
approach has paid dividends. Not only is its sales force better equipped and
collecting important management information, it has built on its experience.
'We have managed to take everyone across so far and we are now in the final
stages. Even the hardened sceptics who said 'we will never use computers'
have been won over and see it as part of their sales pitch now,' adds Mr
Crick.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIX
</PAGE>
