<DOCNO>FT923-14594</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1ADWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (37): 'Everything gets hyped' -
Software development
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVEN SONSINO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE delegates at a Nato conference in 1968 bequeathed to the computer
industry something far more valuable than any item of 1960s hardware. They
left a philosophy and a name: software engineering.
The chief concern at the conference was how should large scale software
systems be built in the 1960s? Significant projects of the day missed their
deadlines, sometimes by years, and they often failed to stay within budget.
The answer, said Nato, was software engineering, an array of development
technologies to make computer programming a true engineering discipline, no
longer a black art.
Two decades later, the real cost of developing software is still immense. By
1995, world-wide software development costs, growing at about 12 per cent a
year, are expected to top Dollars 450m.
Even small improvements in productivity can still significantly reduce
costs, especially in the area of large real-time systems, those used in
avionics and manufacturing systems, for instance.
With the emphasis firmly on engineering, rather than intuition, it is not
surprising that software developers have now become adept at devising and
using software tools to help them in their task.
These can be project management programs or relational database management
systems, sometimes known has fourth generation languages. However, many
programmers put too much emphasis on tools at the expense of the programming
methods which they support, methods such as SSADM and Yourden.
With greater software developments taking place on pan-European projects, it
is in the everyone's interest to talk the same development language, and to
this end a Euro-method has been on the table for years.
As usual, however, Euro-infighting has stalled any decision. Britain is
calling for more elements from the British method, SSADM, while France
prefers the chic of its method, Merise. As yet there is no sign of
compromise.
The most discussed formal programming style of recent months is
object-oriented programming which can be used to dived large programming
tasks into manageable chunks.
It can also 'hide' certain information, generating opaque software bases
that do not allow the user to see beyond them. A simplistic view of an
object-oriented environment would be Apple Macintosh's graphic user
interface, where users can move files and data around without knowing
exactly what or where the data really are.
Vendors are promoting object-oriented techniques fiercely and this in itself
may turn off some potential buyers, says Barry Daniels, head of consultancy
at the National Computing Centre's software engineering section: 'I think it
has suffered a lot of hype, but it's hype with a bit of substance behind
it.'
One of the reasons developers feel good about object-oriented techniques is
the news that IBM and Apple have committed Pounds 2bn to a joint venture,
Taligent, to develop Pink, Apple's previously proprietary object-oriented
environment.
Other vendors are working on object-oriented development systems, or
object-oriented interface builders, says Apple, which only attack one part
of the problem.
Next's Nextstop environment, for example, is object-based, but only deals
with a small part of the application developing the user interface.
'The Taligent system, however, is a whole new environment for developing
software but it will be 1995 and beyond before it achieves any critical mass
in the market,' says Steve Everhard, Apple's national and corporate
marketing manager. Some users might therefore see the venture as an attempt
to lock users into Apple or IBM product lines, for fear they will be barred
from taking advantage of future developments.
Mr Everhard disagrees - 'this is not a market-stalling activity. This is not
an architectural announcement that's intended to stifle the market. Quite
the opposite. What we're intending to do is give companies and users
confidence that they won't be excluded, on a technology standpoint, from
what we're doing in the future.'
Barry Daniels at the NCC sees the joint venture from a different
perspective: 'IBM put the PC on to the market place, but MS-Dos took over
from PC-Dos. In addition, OS/2 hasn't taken off and Microsoft's Windows 3 is
around. So IBM, corporately, hasn't got much to offer that competition. Then
it sees Apple being fairly successful in some markets and maybe that's the
answer: an alliance between the two.'
In other words, the deal with Apple is nothing more than a quick fix to keep
users tied to an IBM growth path.
Whatever the industry's view of the IBM-Apple venture, there is little doubt
that object-oriented programming will have a large part to play in software
development.
Oracle, the US relational database vendor, has launched object-oriented
extensions to its SQL tools. However, it felt reassurance was in order for
users attending the European Oracle Users Group in Cannes earlier this year.
'It is very important, as we move to object-oriented technology, that we do
not abandon our user base or the investments already made,' says Larry
Ellison, Oracle's president and chief executive.
Mr Ellison's point about not abandoning investments is sound, for the
investment in developing software is substantial: first, in acquiring the
tools and the hardware resources to use them, but also in training time.
Investment in a hotch potch of tools, no matter what the vendors say, is
wasteful and ineffective.
But as long as users listen, the hype will continue, because now, almost 25
years after the Nato conference that created software engineering, the
software crisis is still here. There is still a need for better tools,
techniques and methods and better education and training.
Barry Daniels places much of the blame on the software vendors: 'In a sense,
I am disillusioned. Everything gets hyped. People make far too many
promises, far too early and perhaps far too optimistic benefits from
relatively small advances.'
'That is really the frustration. It's a pity, but it does seem to be a fact
of life in the IT world.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-14595</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1ADVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (36): Tying the knot between
training and the needs of business - Analysis / Companies can choose from a
wide range of training options to support new software applications, ranging
from traditional 'blackboard-and-chalk' to advanced multimedia technology.
But increasingly the emphasis is on the end result, rather than on the way
it is achieved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (IT) has had an enormous impact on training and
education in the last decade. Computer-based training (CBT) packages for
personal computers have spread computer skills, techniques for creating
training material have improved and people are generally more receptive to
the idea of learning from a computer.
CBT has been especially effective in training novice users of personal
computers in basic skills. The art of 'wordprocessing,' or the skills
involved in designing a useful spreadsheet, can be presented in a simple
instruction package and easily absorbed by users. All popular software
packages nowadays come with several diskloads of CBT tutorials and a wealth
of instruction manuals and back-up material.
Despite these developments, the tried-and-tested training methods of the
past are still in wide use - particularly if users want to get the most out
of their 'home-grown' application systems or when they need to train non-IT
staff.
If CBT is used, it is used as part of comprehensive training package which
includes 'blackboard and chalk' sessions, self-study and workshop
discussions.
There is, it seems, still room for the human touch -and, if anything, the
need for good lecturers, tutors and teachers is as important as it ever was.
'CBT is great back-up - but it needs a dynamic person acting as a tutor to
help people get the most out of it,' says Rosalyn Stein, a director of
training specialist Stein-Hodgins.
'It is good for reinforcing what has been learned in lectures and workshops.
The technology is really just icing on the cake - a bit of multimedia or a
bit of animation helps - but it can't do the whole job.'
Stein-Hodgins devises tailor-made training programs for customers who use
Microsoft's Windows environment. Ms Stein goes on to say that the demand is
for 'customised training which fits in with wider business aims.
'We aim to get people productive with an application as quickly as possible.
It is not just training; it is making sure that the training is relevant to
the aims of the business,' explains Rosalyn Stein.
Richard Atkinson, head of FI Group's training subsidiary FI Training, takes
a similar view: 'We see CBT as offering a useful set of tools. But you must
see what the training needs are and develop a training programme which fits
them.'
Market research backs this up, pointing to greater emphasis on the
end-result of training, rather than on the method used to achieve it.
'There are clear indications within the marketplace that demand for training
is moving from technology in isolation towards a requirement for
consideration of commercial and strategic issues,' says the research group,
IDC, in its recent report on the UK IT training market.
Although revenues for IT training suppliers in the UK fell by three per cent
in 1991, IDC says there is a still a strong demand.
It also notes that most organisations look outside for their training needs.
The training demand varies from sector to sector. Central government is the
top consumer, with 87.9 per cent of the IDC sample using external training
services. About 80 per cent of financial institutions use external training,
and the mining and construction sector uses the least amount; only 58 per
cent.
IDC sees management training for IT staff as one of the key growth areas and
also notes a latent market for general IT appreciation for non-IT staff -
although it suggests that the recession will hold back growth in this area
in the short term.
More important are the observations that training must show a genuine
cost-benefit, and must be related to business needs. Users want to see
productivity gains and improved performance coming from their training
investments. IDC notes that training organisations will need to 'align
training with service products that meet demonstrable business need.'
This is especially true with training staff who are to use custom-built
software applications. These applications are often most likely to be the
basis of any strategic IT system. Training staff to use generic software -
like spreadsheet programs and wordprocessors - is much less demanding and
can be accommodated within CBT tutorials and self-study. But the specific
nature of custom-built applications requires specific training and, here,
the old methods prevail.
There are sound economic and eminently practical reasons for this.
Good CBT tutorials are costly to produce. So, if the investment is to be
worthwhile, a tutorial must have a large potential audience.
Most custom-built applications are used by only a small number of people -
which means that it is uneconomical to use CBT.
It follows, therefore, that training staff to use custom-built software
applications, demands custom-built training materials - which are cheaper to
produce with the traditional approach.
The obvious starting point for custom-built application training is, of
course, the application supplier. Users recognise that the builders of the
custom application system are in the best position to train those who are to
use it.
FI Group's decision to acquire Kernel Training last year was typical of the
gambits that service companies are using to get into the training business.
The FI Group is an established custom software developer and saw good
reasons to expand its training resources: 'Training has always been an
important part of the service industry. We saw that the primary route in to
it was through acquisition. And we wanted to take Kernel Training and expand
into a more general role within the FI Group,' says Mr Atkinson of FI
Training. Services suppliers are keen to exploit this useful 'add-on' market
and are, increasingly emphasising training as part of a full systems
integration service.
This market has also attracted established hardware manufacturers such as
ICL and Siemens Nixdorf.
Hardware builders have a long tradition of providing technical training to
customers. They are now looking for ways to extend their existing training
services into the applications area and have chosen CBT packages as one of
their tactics.
ICL recently signed the distribution rights for a multimedia authoring tool
called Authorware to support its training initiatives.
Nationwide Building Society is an early customer and is using the package to
create training materials for cheque-clearance procedures. Siemens Nixdorf
introduced its SITE CBT package earlier this year - with the aim of making
it easier for users to produce good-quality training materials for their
internal applications.
SITE can work across a range of different hardware - making it possible to
distribute training materials in the same way as the software itself. Even
more promising is the looming prospect of multimedia technology - which
seems destined to have its greatest initial impact in the training area.
Some users are taking the lead in the use of multimedia - but once again
within the context of a wider training strategy.
The Bradford and Bingley Building Society set up a training project back in
1990 which uses a Sony interactive video (IV) system to train its staff in a
variety of skills. The building society wanted to see a pay-back from the
system within two years and recently claimed to have achieved this. But
despite the cost-benefits from the IV system, it is still seen as only one
part of a much wider training strategy.
'Our training is a mix of media because each type of delivery has its
benefits. Disadvantages of IV occur if you try and use it for everything;
it's no good for a target audience of five people, for example,' says Philip
Hunter of Bradford and Bingley's training department. He goes on to say,
however, that it is not just cost savings which are driving users to look
for new training methods - 'we are saying that if we don't adopt these
alternative methods of training, we will have to recruit more staff in order
to cover our training needs. In fact, IV methods are sometimes the only way
that training can be done.'
This supports the view that successful training of staff in the use of new
software lies in combining traditional methods with advances in technology.
And as computer technology continues to improve and becomes easier to use,
the emphasis in training will shift from the technology to the application
and the demands of the business.
SEE BACK PAGE: graphical user interfaces (GUIs) bring training advantages
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
