<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1ADUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (34): Still a new market -
Groupware Products
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALTHOUGH there are increasing numbers of software packages which are claimed
to be groupware products, this is still a relatively new market. Two of the
most innovative products in the UK are Lotus Notes and FCMC's Staffware,
writes Philip Manchester.
Lotus Notes has attracted significant support from large consultants such as
Arthur Andersen, Touche Ross and Coopers and Lybrand Deloitte, all of which
are developing systems based on Lotus Notes. Customers include BP, General
Motors and Lloyds Bank.
Lotus Notes provides a groupware application environment for use in personal
computer networks. It contains the bones of groupware applications and
programming features which can be used to create customised applications. It
can be used for applications such as customer tracking, status reporting,
project management and what Lotus calls 'collaborative free-form
discussion.'
Although the roles of many corporate head offices are being devolved and
modified, more controls are nevertheless needed to ensure that decisions
which are made at various levels - ie closer to the customers - are not
eventually detrimental to other parts of the organisation, explains Winston
Muktarsingh of Coopers and Lybrand Deloitte.
'This requires controls on information-flows in very quick time. Lotus Notes
helps to facilitate this,' he adds.
Like most groupware products, Notes uses the client/server model of
computing which separates the 'front end' of an application from the 'back
end.'
The user or 'client' sees a screen with a graphical user interface (GUI)
similar to any other personal computer application. Under the covers, Notes
links to services such as database management systems and electronic mail
which are powered by other computers known as servers.
These servers can be located in the same office or across the network.
Lotus Notes can handle different data formats which are produced by other
software packages - processing documents and tagged image format files
(TIFF).
Notes works with both of the main PC networking systems - Novell's Netware
and OS/2 LAN manager.
Price: from Pounds 395.
Further enquiries: Lotus Development (UK), Lotus Park, The Causeway,
Staines, Middlesex, TW18 3AG. Tel. 0784 455445.
Staffware: this system can be used to set up 'workflow' procedures with
rules which can be applied to the flow of data. This can be something as
mundane as the procedures in an accounts department to complex quality
control procedures manufacturing.
Like Lotus Notes, Staffware can be used with existing software such as
databases and wordprocessing programs or complete office automation systems.
The Staffware rule structure accommodates deadlines to ensure that
procedures are completed by staff using the system. Staffware will send
reminders if deadlines are missed. The system also keeps track of progress,
giving management an up-to-date 'audit' of the system and the current status
of specific procedures.
Staffware runs under the Unix and Xenix operating systems.
British Telecom uses Staffware to automate its buying procedures, and also
as an electronic suggestion box. The US Veterans' Administration uses
Staffware for document tracking.
Staffware is also sold by ICL under the name Powerflow, and by Unisys under
the name Office Procedures.
Last September, FCMC signed up IBM UK to combine Staffware with the Uniplex
office automation system which is sold under the name Application Pack (AP)
6000, an office automation package for IBM's RS/6000 workstation.
Price: from Pounds 750 per workstation.
Further enquiries: FCMC, 46 Chagford Street, London NW1 6EB. Telephone: 071
262 1021.
Other products: Beyond Mail - from European Software Products (ESP) in the
UK. Price from Pounds 750 for up to 10 users. ESP, 36 King Street,
Maidenhead, Berks. SL6 1EF. Telephone 0628 23453.
Microsoft Mail 3.0 - from Microsoft, price Pounds 485. Details from
Microsoft's Customer Response Centre, telephone 0734 500741.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-14597</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1ADTFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (35): Electronic mail turns into
groupware - Technology Update
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE of the main thrusts into groupware has come from suppliers of electronic
mail systems. The latest version of Microsoft Mail, version 3.0, is being
promoted as a groupware product and WordPerfect has upgraded its Office Mail
package to embrace groupware features.
The most interesting of these electronic mail products, however, is the
recently-introduced Beyond Mail package from US software developer, Beyond.
Beyond Mail evolved from a research project at the Massachussetts Institute
of Technology (MIT). The project aimed to add 'intelligence' to electronic
mail systems by introducing rules for processing messages and help users by
'filtering' out inappropriate ones.
'As electronic mail networks grow, the number of messages flying around the
system causes information-overload,' explains Peter Sketch, advanced product
manager at ESP, Beyond's UK distributor.
'Beyond Mail gives you the power to process electronic messages with sets of
rules which can be turned on and off, according to your needs,' he explains.
The rules can be created by users with an easy-to-use Windows-type front end
(a Microsoft Windows version will be available later this year). Rules can
be used to filter out mail, re-route it or give it a priority and can be
based on a combination of criteria. A rule might be used, for example, to
filter mail from a specific source and give it higher priority. Another rule
might cause the text of the message to be searched for certain key words.
'You can get Beyond Mail to work for you while you are away from your desk,'
explains Peter Sketch.
'As well as handling messages, rules can invoke other applications. Data
might come in the form of a spreadsheet or a database. You can build a rule
to re-format it or update an existing database.'
Beyond Mail provides a 'folder' or directory structure for filing messages,
including what Mr Sketch describes as a 'tickler' file for date-specific
messages: 'You can program Beyond Mail to route certain messages to this
file so that they come up on a particular date automatically.'
Beyond Mail works on all MS/DOS personal computers and supports gateways
into the X400 and X25 networking standards.
In addition, it can link to other MS/DOS applications programs.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
