<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1ADSFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (33):  The promise of truly
integrated systems - Analysis / Spreading the productivity advantages of
personal computing  across an enterprise demands a new approach to
applications software. Groupware offers a promising way forward
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP MANCHESTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE drive for productivity has always been one of the main justifications
for the use of information technology. The first computer systems were used
to speed up mundane clerical tasks like the calculation of the company
payroll and issuing sales invoices.
In the last decade, personal computers have helped to boost personal
productivity. It ought to be a simple task to spread these personal
productivity gains to an entire business enterprise: install a network,
connect the personal computers to it and watch efficiency increase and costs
fall.
Unfortunately, it is not that simple.
The physical connection of personal computers to a corporate network is not
enough in itself to bring productivity gains. A multi-level software
infrastructure is also needed. Network management software, communications
software and usable 'front end' software - such as graphical user interfaces
 -must be in place before the network can be exploited fully.
There is also a need for a different type of applications software. The
traditional approach to personal applications is inadequate because it
assumes that there is only one user of the system, working in isolation. If
networks of personal computers are to be used effectively by groups of
people, the applications software must be able to cope with the interactions
between users and control them.
This is where groupware comes in. Groupware is an extra level of
applications software which aims to create genuine interaction between
people through a computer network.
'The personal computer has given people individual power, but stand-alone
personal computers are not aimed at getting people to work together - even
if you put them on to a network,' says John Matthews, a consultant at
management consultancy, Infact.
'Groupware should do this - but it needs something more. You have to give
people an incentive to use the technology properly. The telephone is a
primitive groupware tool - some use it well and some use it badly,' he adds.
Mr Matthews sees the growth in the use of groupware as a management issue -
a view shared by others: 'Groupware is a bit like a mirror - an awful lot of
work in an organisation is already group-oriented. Most of the technology is
available - so the issue is a management one, rather than a technical one,'
says Michael Skok, chairman of European Software Publishing (ESP), UK
distributor of the Beyond Mail groupware package.
'It is a simple evolutionary step from electronic mail. Instead of just
sending messages, you can share all sorts of information across the network.
You can put some intelligence into the system and begin to automate workflow
and office procedures,' he continues.
The idea of groupware has its roots in research into computer-supported
co-operative work (CSCW) in the US, dating back to the 1960s.
Among others, Douglas Engelbart (the originator of the ubiquitous 'mouse'
pointer) and his team at the Stanford Research Institute carried out
pioneering work in CSCW with a system called On-Line System (NLS).
This system was designed to support a team of people drawn from different
disciplines and the software included a set of core tools such as a text
editor, graphics programs and data managers.
The research on NLS later influenced the work at Xerox's Palo Alto Research
Centre (PARC) which led eventually to the Apple Macintosh and Microsoft
Windows.
Engelbart's original aim was to 'augment individuals doing knowledge work.'
But as networking became available, NLS was extended to support groups of
workers who could communicate via the network - making it the first
groupware.
NLS let researchers work together on a project and develop ideas by
co-operating with each other through the system.
This has been the aim of 'office automation' systems for many years and it
could be argued that groupware is just another name for an old idea. Office
automation systems such as IBM's Officevision and DEC's All-in-one package
provide many of the features that would be expected in a groupware product -
including electronic mail, file-sharing and personal computing facilities.
But although traditional office automation systems and groupware share many
similar features, true groupware goes much further than just providing an
application environment within a network. It must enable co-operation
between staff and extend the productivity gains from the desktop personal
computer to the whole enterprise.
'The problem with office automation systems is that there is a tendency for
people not to use them - they can be a distraction because people have to
learn all sorts of new skills,' says John Matthews of Infact.
'But with some of the groupware products, a lot of the problems are
overcome. A product like Filenet, for example, provides automated access to
mainframe resources - getting rid of what has been somewhat of a burden for
users who do not know the complexities of logging on to these systems.'
In its most advanced form, groupware can be used to co-ordinate an entire
product design operation - with the software providing links between
marketeers and designers, production engineers and cost-accountants. The
theory is that this will speed up the process of bringing a new product to
market and give a company a competitive edge.
This is a far cry from traditional office automation systems and has only
been made possible because of changes in the technology infrastructure.
The emergence of 'intelligent' buildings, which are wired up for networks,
coupled with advanced workstations which can handle different types of data,
has created the physical environment to make modern groupware possible.
Advances in software have also contributed to the infrastructure.
Graphical user interfaces such as Apple's Macintosh and Microsoft's Windows
have made it easier for users to access and manipulate information on a
personal computer. Improved networking and communications software, based on
accepted 'open systems' standards, has let different types of computers
'talk' to each other.
Innovative approaches to the design of computer systems - often referred to
as the 'architecture' - have also helped. The client/server approach - where
the system is separated into components which either use or offer services
encapsulated in a 'black box' - lends itself to groupware applications. The
increasingly-popular object-oriented design approach - which builds on the
client/server model - also offers an excellent foundation for groupware.
Modern software environments can also provide mechanisms to link data across
programs and databases. Microsoft Windows, for example, includes a feature
called Dynamic Data Exchange (DDE). This enables up-to-date data from one
source to be connected to another. So a word processing document can include
a reference to a spreadsheet and, through DDE, ensure that it is kept
up-to-date. Any changes in the spreadsheet will be reflected in the document
automatically.
But groupware applications can go much further. They can also control the
flow of work through a company or a project.
Practical examples include, say, the fulfilment of an insurance policy or a
loan application. Both tasks are subject to procedures which have been laid
down by the company, involve a number of staff and require different levels
of authorisation.
A full groupware package, like FCMC's Staffware or Lotus Notes, can be used
to devise the rules to control the flow of the documentation through a
system and ensure that all of the procedures are correctly executed. The
groupware package can channel the documentation to the right person at the
right time and prompt staff to carry out further action.
Most documents produced in business spend more time in people's 'in' trays,
awaiting approval, than they spend actually being worked on, observes David
Carew-Jones of Uniplex, based in the UK, and one of the world's leading
vendors of Unix-based office systems.
The electronic mail capabilities of Uniplex will distribute complex compound
documents anywhere in the world, instantly, to any number of people for
approval, notification and editing - 'the result is a faster turn-round for
the creation of documents which require input or approval of more than one
person,' says Mr Carew-Jones.
Groupware means a fundamental change in the use of information technology in
business and creates a different corporate culture which is less geared to
the individual and more directed at the enterprise as a whole. It follows
that such systems emphasise co-operation in place of competition.
The depth of this change means that groupware must be introduced into an
organisation very carefully. There are two approaches, according to Michael
Skok of ESP: 'You can use groupware for specific projects or you can use it
for the whole enterprise. But we recommend starting with simple tasks and
evolving slowly. If you go too far - say with an enterprise-wide system - it
is too much of a revolution.'
The project approach, says Michael Skok, is the way that most companies will
take their first steps into groupware: 'Project teams probably already have
natural ways of working which mean sharing data and resources. Groups of
about six to eight people seem to work well.'
John Matthews of Infact notes that the state of most companies' technology
infrastructure will dictate the project-oriented approach anyway: 'It is
going to be limited to a single department at the moment because most of the
products are based on a single technology - such as Unix or OS/2. If you
want to get into groupware which cuts across departments, you will usually
have to deal with more than one technology,' he explains.
'There is also likely to be some resistance because of the control aspects
of groupware. We have looked at systems in Germany and Scandinavia, where
the use of groupware is more advanced, and found evidence of this.'
Like all technological progressions, the introduction of groupware into an
organisation must carry the users with it. They must be able to see the
benefits to themselves and to their companies so that they will be
encouraged to make it work.
After a decade of fragmentation caused by the spread of personal computing
throughout industry and commerce, groupware offers the promise of truly
integrated systems which combine the benefits of personal productivity and
improvements in corporate efficiency.
Groupware could be the basis of a revolution in the use of information
technology which is as significant as the one caused by personal computers.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVI
</PAGE>
