<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (29): Price quotations with -
Case Study / Cambridge Lee, Commodity Company just three keystrokes /
Installation success after initial cost shock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL POWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVEN IF a specific cost figure is quoted for a project, unexpected price
increases can occur.
If you are lucky, these will surface early on, before too much work has been
done. If not, you may find yourself with a partially written system, and a
bill for its completion well in excess of your original budget, writes
Michael Powell.
Cambridge Lee, of West Byfleet, is an importer and distributor of
commodities, such as non-ferrous metals and copper tubing. It uses the
Systems Union SunAccount package on its Novell networked machines.
The company needed a quotations system to tie in with the SunAccount system,
which was already in use. A software supplier which had quoted Pounds 25,000
for the project was chosen. However, after four days' work, the quote was
increased to Pounds 100,000. Although this was reduced in negotiation with
the supplier's sales department, the figure was still more than Pounds
50,000, so the supplier was abandoned.
Finance director David Mulholland had dealt with the replacement software
house, Sapphire, in Europe - 'they had done a very good job. They quoted
Pounds 20,000 for this project. A couple of subsequent additions cost
another Pounds 4,000.'
The development language proposed was DataEase, a relational database
product, which, according to its suppliers, DataEase UK, enjoys the biggest
market share in the UK, with 250,000 users, and is used by 80 per cent of
top companies. DataEase UK and Sapphire were de-merged at the end of 1991,
Sapphire retaining its position as an authorised consultancy for DataEase.
Cambridge Lee's business involves a lot of telephone sales. Every contact
entails quotation and negotiation of price.
'The system brings up a quotation in three keystrokes,' says Mr Mulholland.
'This data is saved and the customer's history updated. If the quotation is
accepted, it becomes a booking.'
At this point, the customer will specify the actual quantities and make-up
of the order. This information is passed to Cambridge Lee's transport
manager, who arranges transport instructions by modem link. The final data
is then exported to the Sun Accounts system, where invoices are generated.
The development of the DataEase system took 55 man-days and is described by
Mr Mulholland as 'quite sophisticated . . .it involves quotations
management, automatic pricing, and movements.'
One of the company's staff who is familiar with DataEase adds reports to the
system but does not make major changes. The system is stable, so there is
little need for further help from its supplier. Although Cambridge Lee has a
maintenance contract with Sapphire (at a rate of 10 per cent of contract
value), David Mulholland sees little need for support.
'The person who wrote the system was our support, but after the first few
weeks there was little need to ask Sapphire for any kind of advice. Their
hotline people aren't familiar with our system, so they can't always help
anyway if we do have a problem.'
The outcome for Cambridge Lee has been a successful system. However, had the
company not been warned very early on of the proposed cost over-run, it
could have been much less fortunate. Many companies have found themselves
backed into a corner, unable to avoid increased charges for the completion
of vital systems, or to go elsewhere for a lower price.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-14600</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1ADQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (27): Improved care for industry
members - Case Study / British Paper and Board / When faced with the task of
updating its data-handling methods, the paper industry's trade group decided
on a system already used by other similar associations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL POWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NOT ALL bespoke developments are enormous, involving huge investments in
software, hardware and personnel. More modest projects can still yield
important benefits for their users.
The British Paper and Board Federation is a trade body which was established
more than 100 years ago to represent the interests of paper and board
manufacturers throughout the UK. It provides members with advice on
industrial relations, health and safety, and energy, lobbies the Government,
provides training, and produces industry statistics.
It used a Xionics personal computer running under the CP/M operating system
for its membership data, and wanted to upgrade this. Systems manager Eric
Kilby says: 'Our existing system was fairly old and no longer capable of
handling our work load.' The organisation decided a Unix-based system was
needed, offering full office automation.
British Paper and Board was open-minded in its choice, looking at five
possible systems over two years. The favoured hardware was an IBM RS/6000 or
a Wyse 7000 machine.
Mr Kilby had come across the software house, Care Business Solutions, at an
exhibition some years before the choice was made, and he remembered that
Care specialised in software dealing with trade associations. The federation
had already decided to use the Uniplex office automation package, because it
is considered an industry standard, well-known to many users. Any software
chosen would need to interact with that.
Care proposed a system based on the Empress database management system to
hold the federation's mailing data, and provide an information system.
Care developed a system for the Wyse 7000 computer which could be run under
Uniplex, appearing to the user as part of that product and called from its
menus. The system holds around 2,000 names and addresses (including 650
Members of Parliament) and is an adaptation of Care's standard set of
modules for trade associations.
The federation has no in-house development department, but Mr Kilby, who has
a background in statistics and economics, has been trained in Empress and
will do further development if necessary. Meanwhile, support continues to
come from Care, with regular contact each week. If any problems arise, they
can be corrected via a modem link between the two organisations.
At present the federation uses the Paradox product on personal computers for
local database needs and for producing reports, but users will be converted
to Empress and the centralised package in due course - 'all information is
held by individuals, using Paradox, but has common data. We can improve our
efficiency and information gathering by centralising it,' Mr Kilby argues.
Other allied bodies for which the federation produces figures, including the
Recycling Information Centre and the Pulp and Paper Information Centre, have
access to the federation's membership information.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-14601</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1ADPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (26): A business-led approach to
performance improvement - Case Study / Welsh Water / The best way forward,
the company's IT managers decided, was to look at what information was
needed by individuals in order to do their jobs effectively
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL POWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONG BEFORE privatisation, Welsh Water was working at improving its
information systems strategy. An approach, known as IBIS (Independent
Business Information System) was developed as early as 1984 to provide an
overall development framework, writes Michael Powell.
Welsh Water has published a brochure describing IBIS. Its mission is to
promote and facilitate improvements in Welsh Water's performance by the
introduction of integrated business information systems - 'we wanted an
overall framework to define how we do systems in Welsh Water,' says group
information technology manager, Jeff Maynard.
'Our basic principle was that it should be business-led, not technology-led.
We assembled a group of forward-looking IT managers to look at what
information is needed to run sections, and we found that there were some
good developments, in pockets throughout the organisation.' The group
decided to look not at IT, but at what people needed to be able to do their
jobs.
The resulting systems, developed over the past six years, comprise around 25
modules, which integrate together, consisting of both package and bespoke
software - 'the initiative has taken us through privatisation,' says Mr
Maynard. 'Senior managers are business-focused and driven, and the IT
department now produces the goods they require. You can't extract
information systems from the rest of the organisation: the key to all our
systems is that the information being reported is consistent right through
the company. We've developed quite a bit of software over the last few
years, and we must make it available to line managers - to help them through
the maze of data.'
The company uses traditional organisation and methods approaches to look at
business processes and make them relevant to business managers. For
instance, if a customer needs a new connection, it must access and update
information all along the line, such as the physical position of the mains,
the allocation of staff, the withdrawal of items from stock, and billing the
customer.
One system developed by the company is the geographical information system
(GIS). This was developed on Intergraph workstations, using that company's
toolkit. This enables software to be built, tailored to the customer's
needs, in which rules are set up to define such things as the size and
fittings needed to make a connection. It interfaces with customer-billing,
service, telemetry and general financial systems.
'We have several thousand kilometres of mains and sewers, so data-capture is
significant,' says Mr Maynard.
Working with digitised Ordnance Survey maps, the company records the
position of its pipework.
Against this must be recorded reports of the condition of mains, and the
materials from which they are built (many of the services are more than 100
years old), and the points of connection.
'This can help to improve our understanding of the way the whole network
links together,' he says.
Welsh Water's approach to development is to ensure that all systems come
under a common integrated umbrella. One of the main aims of this integration
is to ensure that a piece of data needs only to be entered at one point in
the overall system. Bespoke systems are developed where necessary alongside
packages - 'glued together' as necessary to make a consistent whole.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-14602</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1ADOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
-{EADLANE-
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (28): Golfers tee up for computer
guidance - Case Study / Bettagolf/LSI / An ambitious golf products company
hopes it has hit a hole-in-one with a software package to help record and
analyse shots.
</DATE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL POWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOLF CAN BE a lifetime obsession: its devotees spend many hours playing and
analysing their game, endeavouring to improve their performance. Bettagolf
Products provides tools for golfers, enabling them to record, during the
game, which clubs they used, and where, the weather conditions and the shape
and contours of the greens. The results help them to analyse and improve
their game.
These products come in the form of booklets: the Scorecard, the Analyser and
the Greenmachine, which are sold through Professional Golfers Association
(PGA) outlets. Bettagolf's managing director, Alan Wooley, reckons that
there are around 2,000 people using the system, since the company's launch
in November 1991, with each booklet selling for Pounds 5.99.
Golf is a very popular among businessmen, and a lubricant to the oils of
commerce in many parts of the world. In Japan, for example, it is reckoned
that 23m people play. A version of the system running on a PC should,
therefore, attract a lot of interest when it goes on the market shortly.
Development of the software (called Pro-Am Plus) was undertaken by Logical
Systems International (LSI), a software house specialising in development of
database developments - 'we looked at two other houses,' says Alan Wooley,
'but LSI's professionalism and reputation swung it.'
The product had to be able to run on industry standard PCs, and the Foxpro
database package was chosen as the development tool. This allows complete
systems to be developed very easily, using screen-based tools. LSI offered a
fixed price contract, and produced a project plan for the development -
'some software houses promise the earth but don't deliver. LSI kept us fully
informed and all our targets were met. They are a very good professional
outfit,' says Mr Wooley. 'Some extras were added to the product as we went
along, at no extra charge.' The project lasted for around four months: LSI
also wrote product manuals.
Bettagolf has no in-house development resources. It plans to use LSI to
perform any enhancements or maintenance to the product which may be needed
at time and materials rates. Pro-Am Plus is designed to be simple to use,
suitable even for those who have not operated a computer before. On-line
help facilities are available, even though these were not originally
specified.
'To say it is user friendly is an understatement' says Mr Wooley. 'It tells
you what you are doing at the bottom of the screen all the time.'
The software is a commodity item which will sell at Pounds 24.99. At that
price the product must be usable without reference to its supplier, and must
have rock solid reliability.
The use of an outside company for the development of such a system may be
thought to be somewhat dangerous. If problems arise, it may cost a lot of
money to have them resolved.
It would be impractical, however, for a start-up company like Bettagolf to
employ the number of people needed for such a development - the team peaked
at six people. As long as the developer is competent, using an outside
consultant makes a lot of sense.
The product is now reaching the market. Only time will tell how successful
it is; Alan Wooley, however, is confident - 'we wanted it to be as simple to
use as the manual system, and LSI did that for us.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV
