<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1ADLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (23): Excellent management -
Consultant's Critique
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN GRUMBALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'EIGHT software houses - they must be insane.' That was my first response to
hearing about Lloyds Bank. However, I was very impressed by how well Peter
Dailey had made it work. The project ran to time and to budget.
By managing the external resources so well, Lloyds has retained complete
control of all the important facets. The IT staff are familiar both with the
components and the inter-relationships.
The system has become an enabling technology. Although it started as a
secure funds transfer mechanism, it can be extended to a wide range of
transactions. The bank finds itself with a potential electronic mail system,
an electronic data interchange network, and so on. The inherent security is
a distinct advantage over the traditional solutions in these areas.
The key points from this case study are:
Excellent management. What could have been a nightmare has been a great
success.
Awareness that developing a technology can both meet a particular need and
provide a base for future services.
Recognition that the job is not finished when the customer receives the
software. Support, training and an upgrade strategy are all vital for
success.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-14606</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1ADKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (22): LloydsLink - Technology
File
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LLOYDSLINK system uses personal computers in customers' offices linked
to the central switching system, the Logica Transaction Director, based on
fault-tolerant computers from Tandem.
The central hardware consists of three processors which work together and
back each other up. Lloyds further ensures fault tolerance by having a
duplicate stand-by system at another site.
The central system handles messages and links to other services such as the
Chaps clearing system.
LloydsLink facilities available to customers through their personal
computers include balance reporting; statement reporting, with details of
sterling and foreign currency transactions; transfers between Lloyds
accounts; and initiation of sterling payments through the national Chaps or
Bacs services, or through Lloyds, including salary payments to individuals.
Links from the switching system to the external NDC bank network service
enable customers to look at their accounts held in other banks.
Lloyds has not revealed the total cost.
Almost 70 per cent of expenditure has been on equipment and software
developed externally. At the peak, there were 150 people on the project,
including two dozen from Lloyds.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
