<DOCNO>FT923-14609</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1ADHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (19): Objectives have been met -
Consultant's Critique
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL POWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRUST is the key to a good relationship. Once RAC Enterprises (RACE) had
selected its systems supplier, it entrusted the project to Travellog.
This trust continues. Travellog keeps a copy of RACE's software on its own
machine, and has a modem link to RACE's machine. This arrangement ensures
that RACE can receive instant fixes in case of problems. Version control is
maintained, according to Travellog's Andrew Osborne, to ensure that the two
companies' systems remain in step.
Another form of trust is the reliance which RACE has on its machine. RACE
performs an automatically scheduled back up to tape of its data each night,
after its Dover office closes at 11pm. If the machine were to break down -
and it has been very reliable so far - the company could temporarily revert
to manual systems, using the pre-printed forms employed before the machine
arrived. No preventive maintenance contract is in force - such is the
general reliability of such machines these days. An uninterrupted power
supply is installed, to ensure smooth close-down if there is a power cut.
RACE publishes a brochure describing its system, in which it makes a great
deal of the system's usability. The conventional IT-oriented view of
usability is that there should be uncluttered screens, lots of help
messages, probably a graphical user interface (GUI), with colour and fast
response times. RACE's system scores on the first and last points. However,
it does not offer help messages, use a GUI or colours.
This bucking of the conventional wisdom makes a comment on that wisdom. This
system requires that its users are trained in its use. They must know their
product, because they must be able fluently to answer their callers. Help
messages would mainly be of use to untrained users, so are superfluous.
The company uses OS/2 PCs as terminals in its main office, to allow users to
link both to its own system and to its parent's mainframe membership
computer. These PCs are capable of both colour and graphics. However,
graphics would add nothing to a system like this, which is menu driven, and
aiming for fast response times. Colour might be useful better to highlight
parts of the screen - Andrew Osborne admitted that the system was capable of
supporting colour displays.
RACE's trust in its suppliers has so far paid off. Its system has met its
objectives, appears stable and has contributed to company growth.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-14610</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1ADGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (18): Travel booking system -
Technology Profile
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The booking system runs on a Pounds 50,000 IBM RS/6000 computer under IBM's
AIX version of the Unix operating system.
There are 30 IBM PS/2 personal computers at the Croydon office linked to the
machine and two terminals in Dover, which handle last-minute bookings.
The PS/2s are connected via a local area network which also links to the
RAC's central IBM 3090 mainframe computer in Milton Keynes. This is to allow
reservations staff to check RAC membership numbers in case of doubt, for
example where claims are being made for special discounts.
The system leads the reservations person through the booking and selling
process, for example moving from the reservations screens to the insurance
screen and immediately filling in the caller's personal details in the
relevant places on the new screen.
A move from one screen to another is done at the touch of a single key.
System response is instantaneous. The only time callers become aware of a
slight delay is when the system dials out to a ferry operator's computer.
The travel services unit also has a Pounds 110,000 automatic call
distribution system from STS, now used as standard across the RAC. It has 30
outside lines and 24 internal stations.
Calls can be directed to individuals or groups, with or without delays. The
RAC says the system produces comprehensive management information.
The total project, including equipment, cost Pounds 600,000.
Half the total went to Travellog, although this included the cost of the
RS/6000 and the personal computers.
</TEXT>
