<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (10): Aiming for all round
benefits - Case Study / Hambros Leasing/CHP Consulting / New, easier-to-use
system will provide better information and cost-savings, too
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN HAMBROS Leasing started work on a new administration system, it decided
straightaway that it could save money if the system could later be sold as a
package to other leasing specialists.
That decision is set to boost the system developer, a small, young software
company called CHP Consulting, by giving it its first entry into the
software products business.
Hambros Leasing, a subsidiary of Hambros Bank, describes itself as a
medium-sized operation handling medium-sized business, typically funding
capital investments of Pounds 1m and above. It also manages other companies'
leasing portfolios. Its income was Pounds 106.8m last year, and it has 36
staff at its headquarters opposite the Tower of London.
Hambros Leasing started life in 1983 with a Wang VS/100 business
minicomputer running the Leasepac software package from Andersen Consulting.
'In the early days, the leasing business was driven by tax allowances and
leasing companies offered very much a standard product,' says Mr Tony
Curtin, a director of Hambros Leasing, 'but when that all changed with the
1984 Finance Act, we had to become more flexible to write and retain
business.'
Leasepac had been written in 1980, when the old rules applied - 'no
transaction is the same as any other these days,' Mr Curtin says. 'This
means we spend a lot of time doing things manually and trying to get round
the system so it can cope with what we are doing. This has been happening
more and more: staff have been spending late nights doing things they
shouldn't have to do, because of the system. Andersen have been in
constantly to upgrade our system.'
Andrew Page was the man doing much of that upgrade work for Andersen. In
1990 he left the company to become the 'P' in CHP Consulting, which was set
up in May that year with two other financial computing specialists from
Andersen: Justin Cooper and Ian Hargrave. The company now has 10 staff and
had a turnover last year of Pounds 410,000. It concentrates on consultancy
and systems in the leasing and asset finance business.
IN October 1990, Hambros Leasing decided the time had come to get a new
administration and treasury system. The treasury function was being handled
by a combination of a box of cards and the Lotus spreadsheet package running
on personal computers outside the administration system.
'We wanted improved ease-of-use and better information, but we had to have
real cost-savings as well,' says Mr Curtin says. 'That did not necessarily
mean through job cuts, but rather by expanding our existing business and
moving into new areas with the same number of people.
'In addition, on the treasury side we didn't think we were getting enough
efficiency from our funding. This is a very competitive business: almost 30
per cent of all new capital expenditure in the UK is leased, but all the
clearing banks, most merchant banks, and many equipment and other asset
suppliers offer leasing services, so we need to look at opportunities to cut
funding costs.
'Another consideration was that Wang was in fairly deep trouble, so we
wanted to replace the computer.'
Hambros Leasing's knowledge of Andrew Page's work while he was at Andersen
led the company to call in CHP to look at the options for the way ahead.
'In the past computing had been considered in isolation, largely because of
the inflexibility of the package,' Mr Page says. 'There was no
consideration, for example, of integrating the automation of all areas to
get maximum benefit from the overall system. So our study looked at the
total business, the bigger picture.'
CHP says there were four or five packages available but these were mostly
either old or reworked from old systems.
In January 1991, Hambros Bank's central information technology steering
committee decided to commission CHP to design a new bespoke system for an
IBM AS/400 business minicomputer - 'we didn't consider any other bespoke
software companies,' says Mr Curtin. 'We knew that CHP understood the
business, which was important.
'We also knew we would get high-level people, whereas with a big company we
might have high-level people at the very top but they might devolve the real
responsibility to others who might not know our business and could get into
problems.'
A key issue was the possibility of the software developer turning the system
into a package which could be sold to others - 'this was always in our mind,
right from the start in October 1990,' Mr Curtin says. 'The costs of bespoke
system development would be too great unless you were one of the very
biggest players. We agreed terms with CHP which were substantially lower
than if we had gone for a one-off development.'
CHP says it was happy with the arrangement - 'we saw there was a market need
because the business has changed so much since 1984,' says Mr Cooper.
CHP's small size was also something of an issue: at the peak of development
eight of its 10 staff were working on this one project.
'Concern about CHP's size is always there - but we knew from the cash flow
we'd be giving them that they'd keep going,' Mr Curtin says, half jokingly.
'They're big enough now to carry on even if one of the partners was run over
by a bus.'
Mr Page at CHP says, 'We'd been going for eight months when we got the
design contract, so we'd showed we could survive. We have eight clients.
Leasing is a very close-knit community and that worked to our advantage,
because Hambros knew our other clients.'
His fellow director, Ian Hargrave, adds, 'This is our biggest contract. We
haven't got all our eggs in one basket, but quite a lot of them. We're
investing in getting it right, because in effect we're investing in our own
future.'
Hambros Bank has a computing centre at Brentwood, Essex, with a Unisys
mainframe. It has 90 computing staff, including 16 based at the London
headquarters.
'Using them wasn't an option,' Mr Curtin says. 'They are dedicated to the
banking side and have no special knowledge of the leasing business. In
addition, gearing up for the project and then gearing down, would have
created problems.'
The computing department is involved to an extent, however: systems group
manager David Nisbett is in the project steering group. The new system has
to feed information to the central group exposure system and has to fit in
to the bank's overall information technology strategy.
That strategy, oddly at first glance, led CHP to propose the IBM AS/400 for
the leasing system.
'We chose the AS/400 because we are familiar with it, it's very friendly for
development because of its built-in relational database system, there are
some well-established CASE (computer-aided systems engineering) tools
available and a lot of appli cations software packages, notably nominal
ledger products,' says Mr Hargrave.
Hambros Bank is looking towards open systems, normally associated with the
Unix operating system - which is not supported by the IBM AS/400.
'The bank has talked about its commitment to open systems to improve
information transfer but it's also pragmatic and wants bespoke work done
quickly,' says Mr Cooper. 'The AS/400 is good for quick development and has
good connectivity with other systems. With Unix you have to bolt on the
software development tools.
'The benefit of Unix is that you can transfer software from one Unix machine
to another, but this is a one-off development for just one area of the bank,
so portability isn't a factor.'
As well as handling system development, CHP has helped select a new nominal
ledger package, which will be linked in. CHP helped draw up the selection
criteria and identified around 50 possible packages for the AS/400.
'We chose the JBA package because it was one of the few which can handle
different year ends,' says Mr David Shindler, an assistant director in
charge of administrative staff at Hambros Leasing. 'Hambros companies have
different year-ends, but they also have to report for the group year-end.
Price was a factor: it was similar to that of others, but it covered an
unlimited number of users.'
CHP interviewed Hambros staff on their way of working, from taking client
instructions over a telephone to posting items to the general ledger. The
interviews were written up and shown to staff for further comment. From this
process, CHP produced a system description and then a design, which was
approved in August 1991. The AS/400 was delivered in October.
All the development work is being done at Hambros Leasing by a CHP team
sitting in the open-plan general office; development work is done on
personal computers linked to the AS/400 by a local area network. CHP is
using the Lansa computer-aided systems engineering products from Aspect. The
JBA nominal ledger package has been set up, the opening balances are being
keyed in and the system was due to go live in June for the current financial
year. The treasury system is being tested by CHP and Hambros and was also
scheduled to go live in June.
The main leasing and asset finance administration package is scheduled for
testing in July. The target for live operation is next February. Testing of
the integration of the different parts of the overall system is due to
continue until August. Mr Curtin has overall responsibility for the project:
'I was chosen because I had minor information technology experience,' he
jokes. 'I trained as an actuary and that's very computer-based these days,
so I'm used to computing.'
Mr Hargrave of CHP is the project manager. Under him at present are Mr
Cooper, who is the database administrator and technical designer for the
project; two people working on the general ledger; three more, including
Andrew Page, on the treasury system; and two on the main asset finance
system, all from CHP.
Mr Hargrave says CHP is balancing bespoke work against package development.
'We make sure that as much as possible can be driven by parameters,' he
says. 'When we come to package it up, we will take out certain special
things which Hambros has requested and put in other things that might be
needed.'
Mr Cooper adds: 'Between the three of us we have 25 years' experience of 40
banking and leasing companies, so we feel we know what the market wants.'
There is also a user team of David Shindler, plus assistant financial
controller Miss Maureen O'Connor and administrative staff supervisor Mr
Michael Hoffman, who spend 80 per cent and 50 per cent of their time
respectively on development and testing - 'this is affecting the rest of the
11 administrative staff, who have to work harder,' says Mr Shindler. 'The
extra work is balanced by their interest in the new system: they work in the
office alongside CHP, so they're aware it's going on . . . initially, there
was concern about possible job losses but we tell people that the system
means they will be able to work more quickly and take on more, as our
business grows.'
Part of that business growth is expected to come from taking on other
companies' leasing business, running what Tony Curtin calls a facilities
management service, including computer processing of all the administration,
and offering services such as chasing arrears.
And, as Hambros had in mind from the start the cost benefits of getting CHP
to develop its system as a package, so, too, it was thinking about future
business expansion. For although the main system will not go live until next
year, Mr Curtin says: 'We got an AS/400 which is much bigger than we need,
partly with facilities management in mind.'
</TEXT>
