<PROFILE>_AN-CGGB1AC6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920707
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (9): Four hundred sensors monitor
production - System Profile
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE are 400 sensors continuously monitoring 10,000 variables in the steel
and tube-making process at Vallourec's Saint-Saulve plant, linked to a
controller supplied by French company, April.
This machine and an automated furnace controller are connected to three
communications processors from the US company, DEC.
These processors are linked in turn through an Ethernet local area network
to three DEC Microvax computers, which control the production process,
analyse the data and send information over the Ethernet network to operators
equipped with Sun Microsystems workstations.
If one Microvax goes out of action, the other two automatically take over
the workload.
At worst, one machine can handle the entire workload, although response
times at the operator workstations would be slower.
Also attached to the network is a fourth Microvax which controls the
database of 96 hours' worth of production data.
Finally, there are links from the overall system through one of the network
processors to a Concurrent Computer minicomputer running business systems
such as order processing.
The system gives steel plant operators information about the production
process and alerts them if a variable such as temperature goes outside
specified limits.
If that happens, it consults a table to find which associated variables it
should analyse to determine what might be wrong and suggests corrective
action to the operators.
If they do not acknowledge the alarm, then the system tries again - and, on
the third alarm, it will automatically take the corrective action itself.
All the data relating to 96 hours' production is captured to give a
management view of how manufacturing is progressing and to help pinpoint
possible problem areas.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
