<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (4): Packages versus bespoke
systems - Software Debate / Alan Cane explains why bespoke systems still
have an important role in business operations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LARGE software projects involve a level of complexity which is invariably
difficult to manage. It is all too easy to lose sight of the original
business objectives which led to the decision to initiate a new software
development.
That danger is multiplied several times over when the work extends in time,
and headcount rises. Kit Grindley of the London School of Economics quotes a
typical complaint in his book Managing IT at Board Level*: 'As a programming
manager, you need to rewrite Parkinson's Law. Programming work expands to
fill the capacity of the computer enhancement you were foolish enough to
mention, this year's budget plus any of next year's you can bring forward,
and the user's patience to bursting.'
People and ideas change. The longer a software development is in gestation,
the greater the chance that the original purpose for which the software was
designed will have altered - or disappeared. The original champions of the
project may have changed jobs, lost their enthusiasm or simply moved on to
the next opportunity.
These are some of the cultural - as opposed to practical - reasons why
packaged software has increasingly replaced bespoke software in large as
well as small organisations.
The practical reasons are well understood. Packages sold in volume cost a
fraction of a bespoke development. They can be installed in a fraction of
the time needed for a bespoke system. And they bring a sense of discipline
to many organisations in that the company's business processes have to be
adapted to the package, rather than the other way about. All of this
explains why consultants such as Mr Alan Braithwaite, a partner in Logistics
Consulting Partners argues: 'The days of developing custom software have
almost gone'.
Yet as this issue of Software at Work illustrates, there is still a place
for bespoke programming although at a much reduced level than hitherto, (see
next page).
Mr Braithwaite, whose company specialises in the management of materials -
storage, handling and transportation - is chiefly concerned by the
complexity of large projects, especially where a multinational company, that
is, one with separate operations in a number of different countries, is
attempting to become an international operation sharing business processes
and systems across all its activities. One of the great barriers to
integrating separate operations internationally, he points out, is the
difficulty of matching dissimilar systems with separate ways of, for
example, describing data or managing interfaces.
The striking success of SAP, a German software house which has developed a
highly integrated software package to support manufacturing, distribution
and financial management, illustrates the point.
It is used by a number of the world's largest companies including ICI, Esso,
Mobil and British Rail in the UK. Of the 100 largest industrial corporations
in West Germany, 70 are SAP users. ICI, in fact, has decided to standardise
on SAP software worldwide. It has established global remits for the key
components of information technology. These include data languages and
codes, integrated applications for core business functions and computer
hardware. SAP fits the requirement of ICI and other global players by
providing a single data repository, consistent data definitions, one-time
data input and real-time operation across all critical business functions.
SAP represents, therefore, the best of breed in large integrated packages.
Touche Ross, the management consultants, surveyed SAP users and found only
17 per cent of customers unhappy with the package while 67 per cent would
choose SAP again.
But the effort to implement SAP was substantial, Touche Ross found. Typical
users devoted 21 man-months to the selection of the package and of the order
of ten times as much to implementation. This was a consequence of the
complexity of the package and the fact that most users were moving to SAP
from a bespoke system.
The greatest potential benefit from a bespoke system is that it should match
the customer's requirements exactly, unlike a package which is always a
square peg in a round hole (for the purposes of this argument, ignore
personal computer packages. Personal computer users have traded low cost for
the right to demand what they want from a package.)
THE benefits of performing according to specification are of little value,
however, if the system is delivered too late to take advantage of the market
opportunity.
There is a strong case, therefore, for installing a package and trimming it
around the edges until it fits. Mr Braithwaite argues that because no single
package will ever give the user exactly what he or she wants, it makes good
sense to buy more than one and take the best bits from each, again using
bespoke software techniques to provide the glue between the various
elements.
There are hidden advantages in this approach. A wholly integrated package,
because of its complexity and comprehensive nature, may camouflage business
processes ripe for rejuvenation.
The essence of improving efficiency and therefore competitiveness is to
overhaul the processes which determine the way the business operates.
Without business process redesign, computerisation simply automates a legacy
of inefficiency.
Bespoke software work at the interfaces may show up inefficiencies inherent
in traditional practices and point the way forward to better methods.
*Managing IT at Board Level, Pitman, 1991.
The software debate: what do you feel? Letters are welcome on this and other
topics in Software at Work.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
