<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Survey of Software at Work (3): Buzzwords
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Readers who do not have a technological background may find useful the
following explanations of some of the technical computing terms used in this
issue of Software at Work:
Fourth-generation language or 4GL is the name applied to software products
for writing programs relatively quickly. Typically a 4GL program
instruction, often in an English-like form, is translated by the computer
into several lines of a traditional (third-generation) language such as
Cobol.
Computer-aided systems engineering (CASE) is the latest attempt to improve
the speed and quality of system development. A CASE product set might
include: a method for analysing users' needs; a database, (called a
repository), holding program, report and screen specifications, plus project
management information; products for analysing and restructuring existing
programs for possible re-use in a new system (also known as re-engineering);
a fourth-generation language; and a database management system.
Unix is an operating system: the software that manages the internal working
of the computer, organising the main memory, running applications programs,
and handling security and other functions.
Earlier, different manufacturers had their own operating systems, which tied
users to their machines, but there is now a move towards enabling users to
move applications software from one computer to another.
nix is emerging as a standard operating system, running on different
computers, which allows users to transfer software in this way.
Fault-tolerant systems enable application programs to keep running even if
part of the overall system develops a fault.
There are two main specialist suppliers of fault-tolerant computers:
Tandem links two or more computers which can each run different programs but
constantly check that the others are working; if one fails the others take
over.
Stratus, which sells its products directly and through other manufacturers,
including IBM, has a different approach: two processors handle the same
programs and constantly compare results.
Some traditional manufacturers, notably NCR, have launched fault-tolerant
systems and others offer the possibility of running their computers together
to provide fault-tolerant processing.
Electronic data interchange (EDI) is the exchange of business documents,
such as orders and invoices, electronically between traders' computers,
usually through telecommunications services provided by computer bureaux,
which direct incoming calls to the requested recipient.
EDI speeds up the whole process and cuts human intervention and error. It is
currently an area of fast growth.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
</PAGE>
