FT  07 JUL 92 / International Company News: Turkey to privatise 11 cement
companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ANKARA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TURKEY'S privatisation programme is being relaunched with the sale of 11
state cement companies representing around 18 per cent of Turkish cement
production.
Bids, which have to be in by July 24, are expected to raise between Dollars
350m and Dollars 400m. Both Turkish and foreign groups are understood to be
lining up offers.
Societe Ciments Francais, which is now part-owned by Italcementi of Italy,
and Lafarge Coppee are understood to be among foreign groups keen to bid.
Holderbank of Switzerland, Blue Circle of the UK and Loma Negra, the
Argentine privately-owned company, are also expected to make an offer,
together with Sabanci, Turkey's leading industrial group, and Oyak, the
armed forces pension fund.
The two Turkish groups together already control 30 per cent of the Turkish
cement market.
Turkish cement sales on the domestic market are around 24m tonnes a year, or
about the same size as France and Spain. Exports are less than 1m tonnes.
The market is growing by 3 to 5 per cent annually, in spite of a slowdown in
the economy.
The Turkish plants up for sale are at Adiyaman, Askale, Bartin, Corum,
Denizli, Gaziantep, Iskenderum, Ladik Sivas, Sanliurfa and Trabzon.
