<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / UK Company News: East Midlands Electricity chairman receives
102% pay rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JULIET SYCHRAVA
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN HARRIS, chairman of East Midlands Electricity, the regional
electricity company privatised two years ago, was awarded a 102 per cent pay
increase last year.
The rise, disclosed in the annual report published yesterday, lifted Mr
Harris's remuneration from Pounds 114,476 to Pounds 230,969 for the year to
March 1992. The increase is likely to reawaken the row over salaries in the
privatised electricity industry.
Prof Basil Weedeon, chairman of the East Midlands Electricity Consumers
Committee, said: 'I am sure that the general public will be greatly
concerned by such a massive pay increase at a time of recession.'
The chairmen and chief executives of the 12 regional electricity companies
were castigated by Labour politicians at this time last year, when they
increased their salaries by as much as 200 per cent. Most were earning
between Pounds 50,000 and Pounds 70,000 before privatisation and between
Pounds 150,000 and Pounds 200,000 a year later.
Mr Harris, himself, received an 84 per cent increase in the year ending
March 1991.
The latest round of salary increases have been less sharp and the
controversy less acute, although there has been public criticism of some
salary levels.
Mr Duncan Ross, chairman of Southern Electric, and said to be the best paid
regional company chairman, is one example. His current Pounds 220,000
pay-packet is now 253 per cent higher than before privatisation.
Most electricity company chairmen are now earning over Pounds 200,000, and
can earn anywhere between Pounds 20,000 and Pounds 200,000 more from share
bonus schemes.
However some companies, like Norweb, froze top salaries this year.
</TEXT>
