<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / The Lex Column: Asda
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The steadiness of the Asda share price yesterday in the face of write-offs
totalling Pounds 452m is a tribute to the market's faith in the new chief
executive. In other respects, shareholders have plenty to complain about.
The Pounds 350m they stumped up in rights money has been more than cancelled
out, leaving asset value lower than a year ago. The dividend promise at the
time of the issue has been kept, but only for the year in question. This
year the payment will be cut by perhaps a third, with no guarantee of full
restoration in 1993-94.
It is hard to escape the sense that Asda is still living close to the wire.
Net tangible asset value after the write-downs exceeded the limit set by
Asda's banking covenants by only Pounds 30m or so. Interest cover was under
2.2 times, the covenanted limit being 2.0. This year the pressure should
ease, if only because of the Pounds 73m of cash from the MFI flotation and
the fact that the rights issue money will be in for the full year. But the
projection of cash neutrality for the year must be viewed in the context of
murderously competitive expansion from such as Sainsbury and Tesco, which
Asda reckons will cost it some Pounds 250m in sales.
Assuming pre-tax profits of Pounds 100m this year against last year's
pre-exceptional figure of Pounds 86m - the improvement being due wholly to
lower interest charges and loss elimination at Allied Maples - the multiple
at yesterday's 29.5p is over 10 and the yield perhaps 6.3 per cent. Given
that next year is going to be tough as well, that scarcely seems enough to
compensate for the risks.
</TEXT>
