<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JUL 92 / Post Office watchdog urges speed up on reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Post Office Users' National Council, the industry's official watchdog,
yesterday accused the government of backtracking over its plans to reform
the Post Office.
Before the last election the government's Citizen's Charter contained
proposals to establish mandatory service standards and introduce more
competition by reducing the Post Office's monopoly on letters costing less
than Pounds 1.
The Queen's Speech in May contained no reference to proposals for the Post
Office and Mr Tom Corrigan, Pounc chairman, says in the council's report:
'For the second time in barely six months the possibility of legally-backed
reforms had been shelved.'
Mr Corrigan argues that there should be no loss of momentum in putting
Charter principles for better service into practice. In particular he does
not want to see any stepping back from making the achievement of delivery
performance standards mandatory.
The Department of Trade and Industry yesterday said it remained committed to
reforming the Post Office. It added that while it hopes to bring forward
legislation in the next Parliament this would depend on whether other issues
took priority.
Mr Corrigan wants the government to end the uncertainty surrounding its
proposals to reduce the letter monopoly and on the creation of a new postal
services regulator.
The users council is concerned at the closure of 200, mainly rural, Post
Offices in the past year and called for better consultation with local
people. Mr Corrigan says: 'We recognise there must be commercial realism but
that must be balanced with social needs.'
The Post Office said the views of local people were always taken into
account before an office was closed.
The users council also argues that increases in letter delivery prices last
September, up 2p for first class to 24p and 1p for second class to 18p,
should have been deferred for months because of the Royal Mail's Pounds 266m
pre-tax profits for the year to March 29.
Prices have been frozen until the end of the year but Mr Corrigan, says it
is 'unreasonable' that users had to pay more to finance the
'under-achievement' of Parcelforce, the PO's parcels arm. This made a loss
of Pounds 24m, before tax and exceptional items, compared with a Pounds 75m
loss in 1990-91.
</TEXT>
